animal.description:
Meet our new friend, Tucker! 

Tucker's a shepherd mix and about 10 years old. But don't let his age fool you! Tucker loves to play fetch and walk around with one of his favorite toys in his mouth. 

Tucker takes some time to warm up to new people, but he's such a sweet baby once you've become his friend. He's affectionate and approaches his humans when he wants some pets. He also gets the zoomies when he's done! 

Tucker's looking for a super chill, laid-back home without a lot of traffic. Do you have a quiet home, one where Tucker can chill and hang out with you? Do you like to go on walks? Binge Netflix? Then you and Tucker just might be a match! 
If you're interested in learning more about Tucker, please call or text The Pet Connection at 913-671-7387! 

*Tucker is neutered, up to date on vaccines, and ready to go! Tucker is staying in the KC metro, but transport is available to the right home. He's eligible for a no-cost adoption with an encouraged donation.

INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THIS PET? Fill out an Adoption Application now! Appointments can also be made to meet a pet by calling us at 913-671-PETS (913-671-7387).  

ADOPTION INFORMATION:
Prior to adoption, our animals are: 
**Tested for diseases 
**Vaccinated 
**Spayed/neutered 
**Microchipped 

NO COST adoptions with an encouraged donation are accepted. 

The Pet Connection also offers adopters a FREE veterinary examination and a medical care support plan for 60 days after adoption, as well as lifetime behavioral training, safe sanctuary for pets returned in emergency situations, extensive assistance with lost and found pets, and other expert pet services in a variety of areas, including pet selection, behavioral issues, general training, nutrition, and transition to adoptive homes.

Please visit our website at www.thepetconnection.org for more information about The Pet Connection and for a full listing of our available pets, 

Call or text The Pet Connection at 913-671-7387 if you can foster, adopt, or sponsor a special needs dog or cat! 

The Pet Connection is a membership organization operating a no-kill adoption center located at 417 N Rawhide Suite H, Olathe, KS 66061.

animal.description:
DOO DAISY DOO is a strong alpha.  She also is able to clear a 4' fence, so she needs a home where they use electric or only take their dog out on a leash for exercise.  

She is good has developed a strong desire to boss other dogs and should only be in a home as the only dog.  Good on a leash when in control but eventually in a pack she takes over and in a strong manner.  

Kids age 10 and older would be best, but she does love the human company.  

Daisy was a stray back in May of 2019, found in northern Bollinger County.  While waiting for help from a rescue she was chained 100% of the time since they lived next to Hwy 51.  

When with a foster she went over the kennel.  So they put a roof on it and she was content. They let her out to play and she hung around the yard for attention.  

She is at our home now and is also loyal to the yard and out with about 16 other dogs doing well, but trying to become alpha female (with no luck).  

She is hanging out at the door wanting in, making me feel she must have been an indoor dog at one time.  

She is a cutie.  She simply needs the right home to keep her safe. LOVES when I give her attention. 

BEST as the only dog, but again, will do well best with a submissive male. 

Mature weight should be 25-30 pounds.  

Adoption fee is $100. 

To adopt call Marilyn at 573-722-3035 from 9:30am to 9:30pm CENTRAL TIME. Please leave your telephone if you send us a request to adopt so I can contact you! (:>))

We may be able to help with transport. We ship all over the USA. 

You can help us by sharing posts of our dogs on your FB page and by email to friends. 

If you like music, check out our SAXOPHONE CD that is easy listen music that the pets will even like!  Michael Neville donated his CD to help the pets!  Go to our Website to download single songs for $.99 cents each OR download all 13 classic tunes for just $9.99. Simple, fast to do and YOU get something back when you donate to us! 

Want to purchase a hard copy fancy dancy CD (it is beautifully packaged)?  To receive a hard copy donate $20 or more and we will include shipping! 

You can listen to four sample songs at this link: 
http://www.bcstrayproject.org/support-thru-music/ 

You can also donate and get the DOWNLOAD versions at the above link!

To receive a beautiful packaged HARD COPY go to this link: 
http://www.bcstrayproject.org/make-a-donation/

Donate $20 or more then send us an email at   ace@clas.net   and tell us you would like us to ship you a CD.  GIVE US YOUR ADDRESS and telephone number in your email so we can ship and contact you if there are any questions.    

THANK YOU for your support and for shopping for a rescue pet!

We are looking for an adult home and may have to be a female only home. He has been good with my husband but was a little unsure at first.

Charlie has been without a home for way too long.
Charlie was at Knox County for over 450 days when we pulled him.
Before that he was at Pittie Paws where the conditions were so deplorable that Knox County took all the dogs away.
Before that Charlie was with IHAD rescue where he was in a nice foster home with a dog and a cat but that was a long time ago.

What I have experienced is a sweet affectionate dog who like to play with toys, lick faces, sleep and eat treats. Charlie loves car rides, walks and snuggling.

I have been told many things about Charlie from lots of people that have been around him mostly at the shelter. 
I have been told he is unpredictable, aggressive, will need tons of decompression time,prefers woman, prefers girl dogs, was good with a cat, does not like strangers

If interested in Charlie please fill out an application at www.doggiedetour,.org or call me 740-251-8527
Upper Sandusky OH

animal.description:
Hey, everybody! My name is Birdie. This is my second time at TIRR Rescue.

I went home with a super nice family who had a couple kids and pretty active dog for me to play with. However, that just still wasn’t quite enough for me. I’m VERY active and I will need a VERY active family to help me burn off energy! I love playing soccer (I could chase a ball around the yard all day!), so a family with kids who play soccer would be super awesome!

I would do best in a home without any other dogs. While I like playing with them, I get super jealous over my people when other dogs try to get attention from them. I can be a little nervous, and I compensate by trying to make all the big dogs think I’m just as big as they are.

I’m really a good girl, I just need something to keep my mind busy. Playing games and going through some obedience training are just what I need! If you think you might be my forever family, be sure to contact my rescue people!

~~~~

PERSONALITY:
Birdie is a great pup, but she is very active. She will need obedience training and an active family to keep her from being bored. She would do best in a home without other dogs, as she tends to get jealous when around her people.

~~~~

To learn more about Birdie, please visit tirrrescue.org/birdie.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Lassie is a 2 1/2 year old Pitbull and Ridgeback female. She is approximately 80 lbs and has been spayed. She is a fun, loving and playful dog. She likes when she is loved and played with, she likes chew toys and treats. She is extremely loving to small children and has never hurt anyone. She dislikes loud yelling and other dogs. She is in good health, has never had an issue with anything.

I recently rescued a third dog and Lassie began being aggressive towards the other dogs. She has attacked the two others to the point of almost death. When the dogs are out of her sight, she is a sweet and loving dog to people. But we are struggling with keeping her when she is constantly attacking the other dogs. We have attempted to train her and help her for the last 8 months but it has not worked. She would be great in a single dog home. She only wants to be loved and cared for.

My contact information is 530-351-8116 and/or jmkagel3@icloud.com

Simba is a smart, sweet and handsome long haired boy who loves people especially his own people.    For Simba a great and happy day is just trying to please and to hang with his people or family. Simba is housebroken, does not dig or chew and is crate trained.  He gets very excited when its time to go for a walk but can be dog selective and can become defensive if he feels threatened.  He does very little barking but is very aware of what is going on around him.  He would do well with a companion dog or without one.  He could also live with older children (teenaged).  If you are patient and a stay at home person, Simba would love to meet you.
Please visit http://www.coastalgsrsd.org/ to learn more about our dogs. Click on available dogs to see further descriptions. If you are interested in me, please contact us at information@coastalgsrsd.org or call (858) 779-9149. Don't forget to fill out our online application:  http://www.coastalgsrsd.org/webform/1774/adoption-application. The minimum adoption donation ranges from $300 to $400. This amount only partially covers the cost of veterinary care, boarding fees, and other miscellaneous expenses involved in the temporary care and adoption of our dogs and is 100%25 tax deductible. Prior to placement, all dogs will be spayed or neutered, receive current vaccinations, and are usually microchipped. If not, arrangements will be made on an individual basis. Special consideration may be given to those willing to adopt older dogs or dogs with physical problems. Our adoption process begins with completing an application on-line. A phone screening will soon follow, and lastly a home visit will be conducted by our volunteers.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Mickey is one of two dogs seized by law enforcement from horrible conditions in Oct., 2015. He was the more timid of the two dogs and is still quite shy with new people. He is now 6 years old. It does take Mickey a long time to learn to trust people. Even after 4+ years, he is still very hesitant when it comes to being touched a lot. He does seem to enjoy the company of the people he knows and loves to romp and play. He is fully vetted, neutered, and microchipped. His fee is $125.

Mickey will need a very patient and experienced owner who is willing to work with him at his pace. He is still a work in progress. Treats work wonders with him. He needs a secure and somewhat quiet home and does require a securely fenced yard. He DOES do well with other dogs. We think kids over 10 would be best. We have no way of testing with cats. He is our special boy!

NOTE: Adoptions are done via private appointment once an application has been completed and approved.

We are located at 101 22nd St. SE in Austin, right next to the airport. It's exit 180B off of I-90, right off of 218 South.

We do require that potential adopters be at least 21 years old and that any resident dogs be up to date on vaccinations, heartworm testing/preventative, and spayed or neutered.

animal.description: Here is what Chaplin's foster family wants you to know about him… Chaplin (Chappie) is one of the sweetest dogs I have ever met. He is very excitable and does jump a lot, and he will boop your face if you aren’t careful ( he’s still learning all 4 paws on the floor). He is a big cuddle bug and always wants to be next to me. He absolutely loves meeting new people and dogs, and he plays well with dogs of all sizes. He is strong, so he does need two leashes on walks because he pulls (towards other dogs and things), tries to sniff everything, and sometimes will try to jump on people walking by. He is not anxious at all outside in the city, and we walk at least 5 miles every day with no issue. Chaplin is a big, happy boy who is need of a consistent training routine with a dog experienced adoptive home that would not have children under the age of 12. He could live with a canine sibling ( but no cats) who can match his rough and tumble style provided there is enough space and exercise for both pups. Chaplin is ready and waiting for his forever family!

animal.description:
Meet Lacey!

Note: We are requiring at least a home with a 6ft secure fence for Lacey.

Lacey came in with Dakota (we believe they are siblings) when their owner passed away. The family did try to keep them, but it became too hard on them and they asked for Adore's help with finding them a new home.

Lacey is about 4.5 years old and approximately 80 lbs. Lacey was adopted earlier this year, unfortunately, they are looking to rehome her as she has developed severe separation anxiety and needs a home willing to put in a bit of work to help her get comfortable in a new place and routine. Lacey is great with all people and she even does well with other dogs. We are unsure how she does with cats, her foster believes she may want to chase them since she likes running after small creatures. Lacey enjoys a bit of attention and then is content to be on her own. She is pretty independent and enjoys her time outside. She has been around the neighbor's 10 year old son and does well with him.

Lacey is spayed, up to date on vaccinations, microchipped, and heartworm negative.

Jack here! I am a 2 year old, extra large husky mix. Adventure is my middle name and I'm always up for something new. Please note at this time we are doing adoptions by appointments only. Please call us at 650-340-7022 to schedule an appointment.Our hours are weekdays from 11am-6pm and weekends from 11am-5pm (closed major holidays). Interested adopters must arrive at least 1 hour before close. We do our best to update our listings regularly, but we can't guarantee every animal you see is still available. It's also typical for us to have animals who haven't had their photos taken yet, so you are welcome to visit our adoption center and have a look around!
To check on an animal's adoption status, please call 650-340-7022 during normal business hours to speak with an adoption counselor. Emails will be returned as soon as possible, but please allow up to 48 hours during busy adoption periods like weekends.

animal.description:
Mama came to us after she was no longer useful to the people that bred her. At the time, she had a litter of 5 week old puppies but it was clear this was one of many many litters. She stayed with us while she nursed her pups and got back to health, and she's now ready to find her forever home. 

Mama does well with some dogs, and not so well with others. She's been good with small and large dogs, males and females, but also had major dominance issues with dogs of all sizes, breeds and genders. 

We would prefer Mama be an only dog, although she is not considered aggressive. She would do best with someone who lives a very active lifestyle. Mama loves water, swimming, boat and car rides. She listens great on/off leash and would do well hiking, exploring trails, or anything outdoors. 

Mama loves everyone she meets including children, and she has never reacted to a person for any reason.

animal.description:
Perry....where do we start. Perry came from a hoarding situation, where he lived outside and had no human interaction. This boy has been at the shelter for over 4 YEARS! Yes, you read that right, 4 years, half his life.  He has no idea what a home and a family is. The  shelter and shelter staff, is his home and family. Why hasn’t he been adopted? Perry is misunderstood and could be called a recluse. He always hides, when someone comes along, and they never get to meet him. He is very shy, and submissive. Perry is a good leash walker, we are working on winning him over this way. Daily walks are working to gain this boy’s trust. Sometimes he may let you pet him, or take a treat from you! If you’re someone who’s looking for a companion and don’t need instant gratification, please consider giving Perry his forever home. Perry does ok with other calm dogs. A home that is calm and quiet, IS A MUST! With a little love, LOTS of patience and understanding, this diamond in the rough, could shine. ONLY HOMES WITH A PRIVACY FENCE WILL BE CONSIDERED!!!

All animals are spayed/neutered and up to date on vaccinations before going home!

If you are interested in meeting me or want further information, please fill out an application at ochumane.org.

animal.description:
Meet this handsome fella named Tank! He came originally came into the shelter January 7, 2020 when his owner could no longer keep him. He was adopted and now back as of May 2020. He needs a home without cats and small dogs.   He is  1 year  3 months old, current on shots, house broken, now neutered,  and owners said he was good with most other dogs who are friendly. He came in super scared and unsure of shelter life with nothing familiar or normal to him. This can be very common and typically with time they settle in which he has settled in very nicely! He’s super handsome and once out of his scared shell he’s super sweet. Needs a loving patient home that can work with him on basic puppy manners as all pups need to mature into even more amazing adult dogs and help him decompress and feel secure. Might you have the most amazing FOREVER home for sweet Tank?! Stop by for a visit with him today! 
If you have another dog and are interested in meeting another potential new furry member please bring him or her to the shelter and meet on neutral ground before adopting. No need to shuffle the animals around any more than necessary. Please know that 1 mosquito bite can create heart worms and they can be fatal if not treated. It is VERY important to keep your pets healthy and protected by keeping them on a once a month heart worm and flea/tick prevention. These animals are counting on you as their owner to provide them with lots a love and the proper health care so PLEASE make sure you are aware and prepared before adopting. Owning a pet is an extra expense and responsibility but is so worth every minute and penny you invest in them. They will add lots of joy and unconditional love if given a fair chance.
The shelter is open Mon.-Fri. 10-1, 2-5 and Sat. 10-4. Adopt a homeless pet and save a life. If you can not adopt right now come out and volunteer and make a difference in the lives of these animals while they await their FOREVER home.

animal.description: Roxxie IS AVAILALBE (updated 02-02-2021).To meet any of our dogs you must first complete our online adoption application on our website. For more information and the adoption application for Roxxie, please visit our website belowhttp://www.coastalgsr.org/dog_profile.php?ID=21886&name=RoxxieHave you been scouring the internet for a young, gorgeous GSD with more drive than an F-350? Do you need a dog whose ball drive is through the roof? Who will work for a ball, even if it's really only of the felt that actually makes up a ball, because that's all that's left, but she works for it like it's a Kong sized ball with a squeaker inside? Meet Roxxie!Roxxie was born May 15, 2017. She is a very high drive working dog who is as smart as they come, has an enormous ball drive, is obedience trained (knows French, German, and English commands), and is a gorgeous spitfire of a pup. She's happy to chase down balls for hours, is great on a leash, a superb hiking or running partner, and is looking for someone who understands GSDs with this kind of drive. She didn't appear to have been socialized with other dogs and was very reactive when she came to us, but has learned to be civilized around other dogs and did well in a play-group setting. She is good in the house, loves her balls and toys, and needs someone with a low traffic home and GSD experience who understands these high-drive working dogs.Roxxie has IBD, so she eats a single protein rabbit kibble (no prescription needed) and does just fine.The minimum adoption donation for adults is $375 and the adoption donation for puppies is $500. This amount only partially covers the cost of veterinary care, boarding fees, and other miscellaneous expenses involved in the temporary care and adoption of our dogs and is tax deductible. The adoption donation provides that all dogs will be spayed or neutered, receive current vaccinations, and are microchipped. If not, arrangements will be made on an individual basis ( i.e., puppies who will need to be altered by 6 mos old). Special consideration may be given to those willing to adopt older dogs or dogs with physical problems.

animal.description:
Titus is the definition of a big, goofy hound dog. He is a very smart boy who loves to learn new tricks and readily performs for you! He already knows all the basics and has an incredible hound nose, excelling with nose and scent work. He takes a bit of time to meet new people, but, once he knows you, he is always excited to do any activity. 
Titus isn't a big fan of petting, but he shows his affection in his own way and loves spending time with his people. In the right home, he could really thrive. Titus does need to be the only pet in your home. He is part of our Single Pets* program! That means that he is eligible for a free flight home and a waived adoption fee! \
If you think Titus would be a good fit for your family or if you would like to learn more, click Adopt Titus above to complete our survey and be connected with an Adoption Specialist.

*Single Pets do best as the only dog or cat in the home.

animal.description:
Looking to add an active furry friend to your family? Marley may be just who you're looking for! This sweet old man still has an energetic, puppy-like personality. Marley is familiar with basic obedience commands like "sit, "paw" and "down," has great recall and is wonderful on a leash. 
During times of high excitement like getting ready to go on walks, Marley has a hard time containing himself and will often jump, but staff has been working with Marley to help him refrain from doing this. Marley loves meeting and spending time with human friends and would prefer to be the only dog in a family. He's very attentive to his people and aims to please.
 Once he's comfortable with you, his silly side comes out and you'll likely see him rolling on the ground, making silly faces and looking for belly rubs. At 9 years old, Marley is starting to get up there, but he doesn't let that slow him down. So if you're interested in a dog who you can include in some adventures, Marley may be the right fit!

animal.description:
Male Dutch Shepherd-Mastiff Mix

Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Approximate date of birth: 09/02/2015 

Weight: 78.5 lbs

Children: No 

Dogs: Selective 

Cats: Doesn't mind them


Sully is a really cool dog once you've earned his trust. He is big and pretty mellow but has shown resource-guarding behavior while in our care. He will protect anything he deems as high value; this includes food, treats and his "person." What's his is his! He is no bad guy though, in fact quite the opposite. Like all dogs he has a great heart but he came from a bad situation before ending up in shelter and rescue programs. With his unfortunate start to life he has developed some trust issues with humans and we can't blame him. However, once he warms up to you, he will be your best friend.

Sully has a sweet, playful, and affectionate side that has won over every TVR team member. One of Sully's favorite things to do is go on long walks. As soon as he sees you pick up a leash the excitement that comes over his whole body is just a vision of pure joy! He cannot wait to head out on a little adventure with you. He also has a silly side and can be a total goofball. In order to witness this cute tomfoolery, he needs to know he is completely safe and must trust you before he shows that vulnerable side of himself. Sully also likes other dogs as long as they're not too energetic or pushy with him. He wants them to respect his boundaries like he respects theirs.

Because of the resource-guarding behavior and his large size, Sully needs a home with an experienced dog owner and no children. We think he will do best in a tranquil home environment with one or two adults who understand his specific needs and boundaries. Once he finds an adopter who is willing to put in the time to gain his trust and understand him, you will never want to go on another sunset walk without Sully by your side. You will have a companion like no other.

Is Sully the right guy for you?
animal.name: Sully

animal.description:
Male Labrador Retriever-Husky Mix

Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Approximate date of birth: 10/12/2014

Weight: 70.5 lbs Ideal weight: 65 lbs - 68 lbs

Children: No
 
Dogs: Very Selective 

Cats: Unlikely


A very experienced dog owner would be a great match for this intelligent, but quirky fellow! Farley is very sweet with his trusted friends but he can be distrustful of strangers; primarily men. Farley is also suspicious of young children (children under the age of 15) and due to his negative reaction to children he cannot go to a home with children or where children visit. Once he trusts you he absolutely loves cuddles and will seek reassurance and affection (usually in the form of a pat) from the people he values. When in a situation where he feels comfortable, he will still bark at strangers but is usually pretty quick to warm up to new people. This generally happens once he is able to come out to meet them in a calm and controlled environment with a trusted handler. 

When it comes to his dog friends, Farley is very selective. He knows at "hello" whether or not he likes a dog or not. If he doesn't like a dog he lets you know how he feels almost immediately. He enjoys long walks and he's terrible at fetch (don't let him know we told you that) but loves to carry a ball around like he's the MVP. Farley loves car rides and is not an annoying backset driver but a total gentleman passenger. At the end of the day when it's time to relax, his favorite pastime is a hardy bone he can gnaw on. 

Sometimes it feels like Farley is misunderstood. He just really needs a patient and experienced dog owner to love him. He has been in the shelter and rescue environment for so long that he no longer remembers what it feels like to have a person or family of his own. Therefore, he doesn't easily form bonds with people because everyone he has been attached to, has left him behind. We truly believe with the right adopter he will thrive in a home setting! All he needs is a chance to show you what a great dog he is.

Are you ready for a Farley cuddle? Can you help Farley make new, happy memories and give him a family to call his own?

*HEARTWORM UPDATE: Farley has finished his Heartworm treatment and we are very happy to report everything looks good! His energy and activity level are back to normal and he shouldn't have any long term effects from the infection or treatment. It will be extra important for Farley to remain on a monthly Heartworm preventive (such as Heartgard Plus) year round and for the rest of his life. This will help lower the risk of him having to go through treatment again. We recommend all dogs be on monthly Heartworm preventive year round to try and avoid this costly treatment unless otherwise advised by your primary veterinarian.

animal.description:
Zephyr would like to submit his application to be your new best friend! Zephyr is a great mix of party-animal/outdoor adventurer, and at-home hangout companion. Zephyr is great in the house; he is housebroken, fine when left alone, and overall well-behaved. He also knows how to sit and go down, and takes treats gently. He has been working on training with his foster mom and would be eager to continue in his home! One of his favorite parts of the day seems to be evening cuddles on the couch, and he has been a great work-at-home assistant. Zephyr is very friendly with people, and has yet to meet a person he didn't like! He is charming and entertaining with his pumpkin-headed smile, big wagging tail and goofy, earnest attitude. Zephyr also loves getting out and about, and would love to be a walking, hiking or running buddy for someone up for his size and eager strength on leash.  Zephyr LOVES water, so would love to go for a wade or maybe even a swim in the summer.  But he is also happy as can be when he gets to run and play in the yard, so would love to have a fenced-in space to play fetch and do squirrel patrol (he is a little too interest in small critters, so needs a home without cats.) Zephyr is a well-rounded boy who can be active and outgoing, but also enjoys his downtime. He is around 67 lbs and 4 or 5 years old. Email limey922@yahoo.com to set up a meet with Zephyr!
Due to COVID-19, CITY DOGS is currently doing adoptions by APPOINTMENT ONLY. Please visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog to request a meet and greet! 


 Hours:
 10 AM - 3 PM Monday, Wednesday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday
 10 AM - 6 pm Tuesday & Thursday

Fee: $61 | Includes spay/neuter, shots, microchip, license, 30 days free pet insurance (when registered upon adoption)

  The CITY DOGS mission is to increase adoptions from the City Kennel by changing the image of the pit bulls who make up the majority of the kennel population, by preparing all adoptable dogs in the kennel for lives in loving homes and by creating as many opportunities as possible for the public to meet and get to know our dogs for the terrific pets they are meant to be.  
 Our Adoption Process...
Here's a little about how things work:
All of the CITY DOGS posted for adoption are available for direct adoption from the kennel, unless noted otherwise. Some dogs with special needs may require a rescue to pull. You can either stop in during our open hours to meet a dog, or set up a meet and greet with your dog, which allows us to get the dog out of his/her cage for some exercise before you arrive. To set up a meet and greet or to inquire about a dog’s special needs, please email us at citydogs@city.cleveland.oh.us.

About Our Dogs: All available dogs have gone through a behavioral and medical assessment. This assessment is a snapshot of who the dog is at that given time. We cannot make any guarantees with regard to behavior, temperament or health of any City Dog. Most of our dogs are picked up as strays, so we do not know what kind of home environment they were living in (i.e. with kids, other dogs or other cats), nor do we know if most of them are house trained. Everything we know about them is based on volunteer and staff observations. We do have some dogs in foster homes, where they will have more information about how the dog is in a home environment. It is very hard to tell with certainty whether or not a dog will be good with kids, cats or another dog. If you have kids in the home or another dog, we do require that they be present for a meet and greet with the dog you are considering for adoption.
Heath/Vaccinations: Dogs that are adopted directly from the kennel need to go to your personal vet within two weeks of leaving the kennel. All dogs receive their DHPP, Rabies, Bordetella and Canine Influenza vaccines, thought you may be required to get follow up boosters. All dogs come microchipped and with a Cuyahoga County license.

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Merry!  I am a little lover girl at around 30 pounds and 2 years old.  I was rescued near Benson after being tied to a light pole in the middle of nowhere and very rarely fed.  I have A LOT of energy, so I’d really love a family who will play ball with me or take me for walks or runs.  I ride well in the car, potty trained & crate trained, I do pretty well on a leash, but if i see a cat, bird, or squirrel I really want to go play with them, so you better hold on tight!  I really love my food too.  I need slow introductions to new people and new dogs.  I really love belly rubs and when I am wore out, I will climb in foster moms lap and snore away!  I really want my furever home.  I need a family with a lot of energy and love to give.  I am known to get into trouble if left unattended, so my person really needs to be understanding and attentive. If left unattended I like to go trash digging, ripping up papers, grabbing shoes, but I really listen well if I'm caught in the act! I will likely do great with some training, which will be an offer for my new forever family.  I need a big yard for exercise and chew toys to keep my busy and happy. I’m a really good girl who just needs a patient loving family to love me just the way I am! 

Interested in meeting Merry? Please text Gayla with Paw Project at 919-820-3217. Adoption fee is $300 and N.C. adoptions only.

animal.description:
Hi Guero...you chunk of love, you...

"WHOA! What a crazy trip this has been! Here I am, a good lookin' 6-year-old boy who knew nothing, I mean NOTHING... being chained all those years to make babies....then I wasn't! Someone came and got me! I didn't know how scared I was until this whole new world opened up. Do you know it took an hour to get the gross black 3 inch collar they put on me when I was a puppy off??? Crazy! 

OHHHHH, the love (and yea, the training) that comes with being free is the best thing EVER! I discovered tennis balls...oh baby, those are so fun!! Running free feels so good too! Now I know what those deer that came so near to me felt like when I would bark and they ran...I have learned how to make people laugh and even sometimes roll their eyes when I make them think I am coming when called then POOF!, I just run right past...but don't worry...I turn right around and go to whoever needs me... so there is that. 

 I just love my girlfriends! I love to play with them. I can get a little rough but respect when they yell at me...oh yes I do! Some of the boys bark at me...jealous I guess...and I'm not sure if I like them or not...boys can just be jerks sometimes. but I hear I am going to meet some young boys that I may be able to play with and if they are nice to me then we can play and play and play!

 I was, what I hear my people talk about, heartworm positive....but I guess they were surprised when they learned it wasn't bad...I was happy! I don't have any real symptoms they say and am going through slow kill treatment...they also say...and feeling ohhhhh so good! So much that they say is gobbly gook to me...but I get the gist of it all. I am very smart and learn very fast...I just want to please! 

 So don't forget my name....that is G.U.E.R.O. ...hard G...that I do know. Because I am smart.

If you would like to learn more about me, email melissa@dogsdeservebetter.org! She can tell you anything and everything about me!
animal.name: Guero

animal.description:
Luke is a very special to the Misfits family. He has had a rough start to his life and has done nothing but thrive to the best of his ability since day one! He is an approximately 1-year-old bipedal Akita / German Shepherd mix. He is incontinent in both his bowels and bladder and needs frequent baths but he doesn't mind! He was a tri-pod for a while but due to his incontinence, his one back leg was just causing him more problems. We made the difficult decision to amputate his second back leg! While we struggled with that decision, we are confident it was the right choice for him! His personality has blossomed and he has become a completely new dog with the freedom that surgery provided him! He runs and plays with dogs of all shapes, sizes, and energy levels in his foster home and doesn't miss a beat! 

He is not potty trained, for reasons listed above but he promises to pay you in love and kisses for always cleaning up his messes and keeping him clean and healthy! 

He has been great with all other pets he has been introduced to and loves humans of all ages and sizes! He is a little clumsy, so small children will need to be monitored around him. He loves being showered with attention by children of all sizes, though! 

He runs, jumps, rolls around, and over-all just acts like a typical 4-legged dog! He will show you all the love and affection in the world if you will give him the chance to do so! He loves to play but he would also be content to be a cuddly couch potato if that's the lifestyle his human is most comfortable with. 

If you'd like more information about Luke, please E-mail muttmisfitsadoptions@yahoo.com! 

You can apply to meet / adopt this incredible pup at www.muttmisfits.com/adoption-application

animal.description: How's this?  Landon is a lovable, one year old pit bull terrier mix.  He was brought into an emergency veterinary clinic after being found alone with large burn wounds along his back and the top of his head.  With the help of the community, Landon has received the medical care he required and though he may be physically scarred from his experience, he is full of fun, joy, and love and holds no harsh feelings from his injuries.  He has lots of energy and enjoys running and playing and giving lots and lots of kisses.  He would be right at home with an active family who also enjoyed running or playing outside.  While he’s been healing, he’s also been learning some new tricks like sit and stay which he thinks are really nifty to show you… especially if you have a treat waiting for him.  He will need some more loving guidance to learn more, but he’s very smart and catches on quickly.  Landon’s energy and love may be a bit much for small pets and children but he would absolutely adore the opportunity to be your best friend.  Please contact us to find out more about Landon or to apply for adoption.

All dogs adopted through Troy Animal Rescue Project are up to date on vaccinations, spayed/neutered (age appropriate), and heartworm negative. All dogs are given monthly flea/tick preventative, monthly heartworm preventative, and are dewormed regularly. Dogs adopted through Troy Animal Rescue Project are microchipped. Adoption fee is $50. Home visit and vet reference required. Applications can be put in online at http://www.troyanimalrescueproject.org/adopt.php or in person at our rescue center.

The address for our rescue center is 34 County Road 2266, Brundidge, AL 36010. We are one turn off Hwy 167. If you use Google maps, type in Troy Animal Rescue Project and it will take you right to us. Hours of operation are from 10-3 daily. We are open Saturdays and Sundays. No appointment necessary for pets that are located at the rescue center. Appointments must be made to visit pets in foster homes. Appointments can be made by calling 334-508-2367 or emailing troyanimalrescueproject@gmail.com. Location information will be listed beside the pets name if they are at a location other than our rescue center.

Questions can be emailed to troyanimalrescueproject@gmail.com or call 334-508-2367.

animal.description: This adorable little girl came to ARF in 2011 and has been winning us over with her smile ever since! Her cute, wrinkly smile is complemented by a sleek, velvety soft coat. At right around 30 lbs, she'd be a perfect lap companion, as she is very submissive and loves people. But don't let her mild demeanor fool you: this girl if FULL of personality! She gets bursts of energy and will take to tearing around the yard, her springy back legs outrunning her front - hilarious! This little baby will need plenty of exercise, but that shouldn't be much of an issue, as she recently spent an active day with one of our volunteers and did great. Yes, this sweet pup is the total package, but she will need to be an only dog. She tolerates other dogs, but often resorts to unfriendly behavior when left alone. We envision her in an active household looking for a smaller dog that can immediately become a part of the family.

animal.description: Since the Patriots won the Super Bowl we have for you.... from the Patriots starting lineup: Nate! This handsome fellow shares a name with the Pats starting LT, Nate Solder. Like Mr. Solder, our little Nate is an amazing athlete! He loves to sprint and jump around - this is one athletic dog. He'd be perfect for an active family, but will need plenty of human interaction and a secure fence in his backyard. Our Nate tips the scales at a manageable 50 lbs., well shy of Mr. Solder's 320 lbs... but his loving heart is just the same size! Nate was found on Holly Bush Road 2011, the same year of Mr. Solder's rookie season in the NFL. It seems hard to believe that it's been nearly 4 years (I'm sure Mr. Solder would agree) but it's time to find our sweet Nate a home. If this adorable, energetic fellow seems like your type - or if you're a diehard Pats fan - be sure to share his profile.

animal.description: Glen Fry is a German Shephard mix that came to our shelter surrendered with his mother and his sister Winslow Arizona when he was just a puppy. His starfish volunteer likes to carry him like a baby because well he lets her and he likes to show the other dogs how much he gets cuddled. Once he is outside he thrives! He loves to walk on the leash and he warms up pretty quickly (30 minutes and you might be his new best friend). Glen likes other dogs and has been tested with small dogs and didn't seem to notice they were playing while he was exploring the play area. He was in the same kennel as his sister for the first two years of his life and if she didn't decide to tattoo his ear he would still be with her. He misses that companionship in a friend or side kick. He's such a sweet boy and is looking for his forever home that will help bring out his confidence with a little love and affection. Please come meet Glen Fry!

animal.description: Just like the singer, our Beyonce was born in the south. This sweet pup, her mother and sister (Rhianna & Jordin Sparks) were found wondering the streets several years ago. Beyonce is the largest of the three and is the only one that has beautiful light brown markings near her feet. Beyonce weighs around 65 pounds and we believe she is a Lab/Shepard mix. She has cute black spots on her tongue, but remember that labs and shepherds are some of the 30+ breeds that have colored tongues -- it's not just for Chow Chows anymore! She is a very sweet dog that is a bit shy at first, but once in the yard has no problems being hugged and loved on. Beyonce the singer has no problem finding herself in the spotlight, and everyone at ARF wishes her good luck tonight at the Grammys..... but as a black lab in a shelter, our Beyonce is constantly trying to stand out from the crowd. This sweet pup has been passed over too many times, but we know she can be a winner. After all, a home for a shelter dog is the biggest award of all! Please help us promote Beyonce and make this her big night!

animal.description:
As many of you know, we continue to run at full capacity here at the new shelter location on Mayes Street. The new dog pens have succeeded in keeping our rescue animals warm, dry, and safe this winter. The only unfortunate component of this is that we very literally do not have any room to spare. While adoptions continue at a modest pace, it's not enough to offset the steady stream of dogs that we are asked to take. These constraints force us to turn away a number of animals. but there are times where exceptions have to be made. Mayesie is one of those exceptions.

Mayesie was brought to us by her "owners", who could no longer deal with the nuisance of having a dog around. Except, or course, that Mayesie isn't a nuisance at all. She is energetic, playful, affectionate all these things and more despite having a 4 foot piece of rope that had become embedded in the skin of her neck. Despite not having any room for the dog, we were happy to take Mayesie and her "owners" were happy to be rid of her. They didn't even ask for the rope back.

We're so pleased that Mayesie is now in a warm, safe place. Still, we're disheartened because - although she gets multiple daily walks and attention - she's doesn't have a pen of her own. It's obvious that she deserves so much more, and we hope that you can find it in your heart to open your home to her. If your home is not right for Mayesie, we encourage you to come by the shelter and spend some time with her. She loves getting to meet new people and loves any excuse to get to play outside. Come see her today!
animal.name: Maysie

animal.description: In early 2011, three little pups and their mother, June Cleaver, arrived at ARF. June was a loving, attentive mother to her three pups. She was also a fluffy, golden sprite of a dog, and was quickly adopted once her pups got to a self-sufficient age. Though her sweet pups are now grown, not a single one has been adopted from ARF. Beaver is one of these dogs, a sweet pup that has spent his entire life at the shelter. Beaver is truly charming, with a gorgeous black and chestnut coat. Like many puppies that only know the shelter life, he is very close with his siblings but somewhat less certain about people. Yet given his calm demeanor and curious disposition, we have no doubt that he will quickly bond with new family members. Beaver is fairly small, weighing in around 30 lbs, and would be a perfect fit for any family. This dog has spent the first 3 years of his life at the shelter -- let's not prolong his stay a day longer.
animal.name: Beaver Cleaver

animal.description:
After approximately 7 years chained up, sweet King has been rescued and is looking for his new home! His friend, Bear was recently adopted but King is still at ARF. We are hopeful to find a fantastic home for this fun-loving fellow! King is absolutely yearning for a family of his own!

King is a sweet dog that craves attention.... the attention he so richly deserves after living on a chain for so long. Despite a rough start, and thanks to the Monroe Street Animal Clinic, King quickly learned to walk on a leash with his new human friends. More than anything else, he loves to run and romp in the play yard, free from that burdensome chain. His only abiding fear is that of flying bugs -- the poor thing is terrified of them after roughing it for so many years. King is neutered, up to date on shots, and has a clean bill of health. It is not always a sure thing that chained dogs will reciprocate the love of their rescuers, but King has paid us back in spades! He adores any attention that he receives, happily leaping into your arms for the extra scratch. He'd make a great fit in many homes, ideally with someone who will take advantage of his healthy energy level, but we have no doubt that this survivor will bond quickly with any family that takes him in.

For many more photos of King, to include the photos of when he was chained up, click here: https://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.10155558324135424.1073742006.494663480423&type=3

animal.description: This sweet honey bear is Geoffrey, who arrived at ARF as a puppy in 2006. Yes, 2006! Unfortunately he's still at the shelter, sharing a pen with his little sister Buddha. Geoffrey is an absolute sweetheart who adores his sister and any people who come to visit. He's very tolerant of Buddha's sneaky sibling slights, such as nibbling on his ankles or using her superior speed to steal his tennis balls. This modest temperament suggests he'd be a tremendous family dog. His activity level rises well above that of most dogs his age, as he loves to run around in the grassy play yard and chase down toys. He hasn't quite learned to walk on a leash yet, and this can be somewhat of a challenge due to his thick-set, 75 lbs. frame. However, given how much he likes spending time with people, we expect him to learn to leash-walk in pretty short order. Geoffrey has a couple other siblings still at ARF, but if he's YOUR pick of the litter, come visit him today!

animal.description:
Way back in 2008 we saw this very pregnant pup wondering around the Belhaven neighborhood in Jackson. The pup was in bad shape and it was clear she was trying desperately to find shelter so she could settle in and have her babies. Well, ARF took her the ranch, gave her a nice warm bed and a BIG bowl of food. It wasn't 15 minutes after she arrived that she went into labor. That was November 21, 2008. can you remember where you were in November 2008? Seems like a long time ago, doesn't it. and it seems like an especially long time to still be at the ranch. Most of this litter has since been adopted, but two sweet dogs have been looked over time and time again. Meet Greta, a sweet and gorgeous pup. Ever since she was born at the shelter she constantly looks for someone to take her home. Greta has had 3 birthdays with us, and each year we wish that she could have a family that would spoil her on her birthday, and love her every day in between. Her birthday is coming up. again.. and we fear that, again, she will spend it without a family.

Greta is approximately 45 pounds, spayed, and up to date on shots. She is shy at first, but it doesn't take long for her to open up and show you just how wonderful and sweet she is. She loves to walk and does very well on a leash. Please consider giving Greta the very best birthday present this year: a home.

animal.description:
Pet of the Day: Cleopatra!

Cleopatra was found in April 2012 nursing two puppies that at the time we questioned were even hers. She and the pups were in bad shape and were doing everything they could to survive. Once we took them in, Cleopatra nursed those puppies into good health as we nursed her back to good health. Even after those pups were too old to nurse we caught her still being a mom. One morning we came to the shelter to find that she had managed to get into the pen next to her, filled with a young litter, and was nursing them too! Once a mom, always a mom, I guess!

Cleopatra is a remarkably happy, sweet, and submissive pup. Even when she isnt smiling, she still has a very happy smirk on her face. She isn't very large, but is very strong (sounds like a few mothers I know!). Cleopatra has one of the softest coats of our dogs at the shelter and she loves to be touched and snuggled! She's good on a leash and loves to run and play in the yard- especially when the grass is long!

As many moms do, she has put the kids ahead of herself for too long! It's her turn now! We are happy to introduce to you..... CLEOPATRA! Please share her story so we can spotlight her and find her a home!

animal.description:
This is Shamrock!

Shamrock is 8-years-old and was rescued from San Diego Humane Society. He became a Frosted Face on July 31, 2019. From day one, we knew Shamrock would be challenging to place. Our generous FFF supporters rallied to raise money for training, behavioral consultations, and his Molly & Me Project incentive (see info below.) Our volunteers signed up for biweekly hikes and outings for enrichment. We've learned a lot about Shamrock during his time with us, but one thing is for sure: Shammers needs a family as special as he is!

Because Shamrock has been at Frosted Faces for well over a year, many of our volunteers have made a point to spend extra time on him and even take him on outings. One of these volunteers noticed how much Shamrock loves to play soccer and brought him the best present: a bright green soccer ball of his very own with his name written right across it so no one else could mistake it for theirs. She told us, "You know that quirky friend who you weren't sure about at first? But you gave them a chance and realized how funny, loving and special they truly are. That's Shamrock! He loves to play, give you kisses and be silly. He just needs you to give him some time so he can be his true self. He more than deserves a real home and his own person who will love him with an open heart."

For a guy who can be challenging to get to know, Shamrock sure has a lot of people rooting for him! Another volunteer shared, "Shamrock has a unique style and charm that he keeps hidden behind a hard outer shell. But for those with a bit of patience, curiosity, and willingness to give him a chance, he slowly allows that harder exterior layer to crack open revealing his beautiful, sweet inner core. An inner beauty full of adventure and a yearning for companionship. He has the most brilliant and shockingly clear hazel eyes, the sweetest little snore when he sleeps, a cute head tilt when he's curious, and the most adorable soft-sounding bark when he's excited. A soccer pro, beach enthusiast, and an occasional hiker. Simply said - he's perfect."

Shamrock went on a two-week Frosted Fling that turned into a Foster home. For as crazy as Shamrock was in his kennel at FFF, he's a pretty mellow dude in a home. His Foster Mom reports that he sleeps during the day while she works and then is energetic for long walks. He is potty trained and can hold it overnight for 12 hours. They have shared many fun adventures together! Shamrock loves going to the beach for walks and swims in the ocean, and he's also enjoyed hikes in the mountains. Shamrock can be nervous around new people, but as he learned to trust his Foster Mom and has gotten so much better at making friends, including male and female housemates. We are so thrilled to see how Shamrock has transformed with love, patience, and consistency.

His Foster Mom shares, "Shamrock has been acting more and more like a real dog, socialized and able to bond. His personality has evolved a lot over the past 6 months. At first, he was angry, anxious, and scared. I just gave him space and time to feel comfortable and gain trust. A lot of exercise and outings helped. He has a fun spirit. He let's out cute little barks when he's happy and wanting to communicate that he's excited for a walk or dinner. It makes me smile knowing he's more than ready for his forever home. He's a very special dog who brings so much joy to life!"

Shamrock has come so far and is now ready for family! Apply to meet him at : www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Shamrock is is eligible for a $200/month paid foster through the Molly & Me Project.

You can learn more at: www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/mollymeproject

Visit us at Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm

Learn more about our programs at www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family. No adoption fees and we help with medical costs!

Questions: adopt@frostedfacesfoundation.org

Updated: 1/31/21 KG

animal.description:
Hi.  My name is Duckie.  I'm a cute young dalmatian cattledog mix girl about 3 yrs old who ended up in the East Valley LA City shelter in Van Nuys.  Not a fun place!  Luckily Dalmatian Rescue saw me and got me out of there before something bad happened.  I am a happy girl now, living with a group of dogs so I can play pretty much non-stop.  Perfect for a busy busy girl like me.  I am being walked daily so  I am learning my leash manners.   I am shy with strangers but I warm up quickly once I know you are friendly.  I am a nice smallish size, only 36 lbs.  I am spayed, vaccinated and microchipped so I am ready to go home anytime.  Because I am so shy, i would be best in a home without young children but another dog or two would be great.  A dog knowledgeable owner, preferably one familiar with high energy dogs like myself, would be preferred. I am still learning all of the rules but I know, in the right home with the right owner I would become just the most perfect pup ever.  I would sure like that chance!

If you are interested in meeting me, please contact Dalmatian Rescue of Southern California, Inc. by email at dalrescue@sbcglobal.net.  Rescue requires completion of an adoption questionnaire to make sure I would be a good fit for you and your family, but once completed and approved, arrangements can be quickly made for you and your family to come meet me.  I have not found my new home yet but I know it will be soon.

To learn more about Dalmatian Rescue of Southern California, Inc., a 501c3 non-profit charity, and to see all of our available dogs, please visit our website at www.dalrescuesocal.com.  You can also visit us on facebook at www.facebook.com/spottyfriends.  We love seeing posts and photos of life with your spottyfriends so please, keep them coming.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website. All of our dogs and cats are in foster homes and we have no paid staff. If you have questions concerning a specific animal, PLEASE fill out an application and the foster parent will be in touch. We will not arrange any home visits with any of our dogs and cats until your application is processed. Please understand our foster parents are precious to our 2nd Chance family; without them we cannot function, so we do our best to not burden them with multiple appointments. Our foster parents will choose their top 3 applications and arrange home visits with these applicants. The adopter will be chosen at that time. The process can take anywhere from a week to a month. We want to make sure our little furry ones are placed in their 'forever home' and never have to go through a rehoming again!My story had a sad start. I lived with a family that didn't really value me :( They never bothered to get me spay'd so I ended up pregnant. I know I should have been more careful but what's a girl to do if her family doesn't keep her safe?! Any way I ended up giving birth one night by myself. If was REALLY scary and I was running around and 3 puppies dropped out but a 4th one was stuck halfway out and I was all alone and didnt know what to do. Then my family came home and I don't know what happened but the police came and those guys seemed to care more than my family. I heard them keep saying we have to do something before she dies! The were on their phones making calls and they called both emergency hospitals in Harrisburg and neither would help without payment :( WOW :(

Then one of the cops called his wife who is also a cop and she said 'Let me call Lynn at 2nd Chance'. Next thing I knew she came to the house and picked me up (with my 3 puppies), but I still had the 4th one stuck inside me. We took a drive to York and then I was at a hospital and they were very nice and took care of me, but it was very sad that my 4th puppy didn't survive.

The nice lady put me back in her car and took me to this place they call 'The Ranch'. It was such a nice place! The people there got us nice soft bedding and a warm room and food and water and took care of all of us until our Foster Mommy 'stepped up' and took my little family in.

My foster mommy is super sweet and she takes really good care of us. She makes sure we always have baths and smell good and I'm done feeding my babies now so I get to run around the house with my foster mommies 2 dogs and it is SOOOOO fun!!!!

I want to go to a home with another playful, small dog that will love to play with me too since my foster mommy says she can't keep me because she has to save more lives like mine. I think that is really cool even though I will miss her :)

UPDATE FROM FOSTER MAMA: Harper deserves to be at a home where she will be treasured for being the awesome little dog that she is! Watching how she was with her puppies, earns her a 'Mom of the Year Award'! Harper was super attentive with her puppies and spent all of her time taking care of their needs -- even when they got older. She completely trusted us to care for her babies and never showed us the least amount of aggression while doing so. She gave everthing she had to them and now that they have found new homes, she is actually relaxing a bit more and enjoying more cuddle time.

She's quite playful and loves other dogs, and when she greets us, she jumps up and down then rolls on her back with a big goofy smile that melts your heart. She can be a bit protective and barks when strangers come over but she sits down and lets them pet her once she knows we are ok with them.

We absolutely love this little dog and think she's one of the best we've ever seen! If you are looking for an obedient dog with a sweet disposition and Yoda ears, well then she's the dog for you!
Please fill out an adoption application:
Adoption application (Dog)
Adoption Application (Cat)

Please understand we do not adopt out dogs to
families with children under the age of 5. We do not adopt dogs to renters. Some dogs will have fence requirements while others may not.

A pet is a lifetime commitment. The dogs and cats in our system find themselves there, for the most part, because their humans did not have the same loyalty to them as they did to their owners. We do not take the adoption process lightly, and will do everything in our power to make sure the animal is placed correctly the first time around for your sake and theirs. Thank you for choosing to adopt not shop!

animal.description:
Meet this handsome hunk named Bubba! He originally came into the shelter December 31, 2019 when his owners could no longer keep him. He is now back as of January 21, 2021 when he and the other dog in the home were having tiffs. She was older and didn’t want to play like bubba does. Bubba is now 2 years 6 months old, current on shots, neutered, house broken, and just a sweet handsome fella. Good size too 47 pounds. We were told he gets along well with children and most other dogs that share similar energy levels. He loves to go for runs too.  He’s a happy fella who is full of unconditional love to share just needs a person or family to give him a chance. Bubba is a volunteer favorite and one volunteer said “this pup is wonderful and wants to please and make just make you happy.” Just a delightful boy who is full of unconditional love to share.  Might you have the most perfect FOREVER home for handsome Bubba?! 
If you have another dog and are interested in meeting another potential new furry member please bring him or her to the shelter and meet on neutral ground before adopting. No need to shuffle the animals around any more than necessary. Please know that 1 mosquito bite can create heart worms and they can be fatal if not treated. It is VERY important to keep your pets healthy and protected by keeping them on a once a month heart worm and flea/tick prevention. These animals are counting on you as their owner to provide them with lots a love and the proper health care so PLEASE make sure you are aware and prepared before adopting. Owning a pet is an extra expense and responsibility but is so worth every minute and penny you invest in them. They will add lots of joy and unconditional love if given a fair chance.
The shelter is open Mon.-Fri. 10-1, 2-5 and Sat. 10-4. Adopt a homeless pet and save a life. If you can not adopt right now come out and volunteer and make a difference in the lives of these animals while they await their FOREVER home.

animal.description:
Duke is a seven year old male Pit Bull Terrier mix who weighs around 65 pound, fully house trained.

Duke is a seven year old male Pit Bull Terrier mix who weighs around 65 pound, fully house trained.
Duke has been through professional training and knows all his basic commands. He also walks very well on a leash! When you are done for the night and you just want to cuddle and watch some TV, Duke will be right there next to you watching too!!

Duke has a few special needs, which have made finding the right home challenging. Duke prefers quiet surroundings and would do best in a low activity home with no children under 12 years old. He can be reactive to outside noise, so a single family home is a better fit than an apartment or townhouse. He does need a fenced yard to run off energy and/or someone willing to consistently take him on 2 or 3 walks a day, every day. He is on medication for anxiety and for allergies, and may always need these medications. He may also require special food to help manage his allergies. He becomes anxious in a crate and would do better in a home where he does not need to be crated often.

Duke does get along well with female dogs his own size, so applicants with larger female dogs will be considered.

If you are interested in adopting Duke visit charlottespca.org/adopt/ .

***Because our rescue is composed entirely of volunteers and we require a home check for each of our adoptable pets prior to them going to their new homes, local applications will take precedence. We will accept out of town applications, but any family further than 60 miles from Charlotte will be responsible for finding a representative of a rescue local to them that is willing to perform the home check. All out of town applicants will also have to be willing to drive to Charlotte to meet/pick up the pet as soon as the application is approved.***

animal.description:
Such a handsome young man, this is Denver, a 4 year old male Boxer/Labrador mix. He has such a striking smooth black brindle coat with white on his chest. Denver is a large dog weighing 53 pounds and he is in great shape.  

Denver had been pulled a couple of years ago by us from our local shelter where he had been down there for 4 months. He was such a good dog at the Shelter, they used him as their behavior test dog with other dogs! We adopted him out over 2 years ago but unfortunately he was returned. He was well loved and cared for but the owner had to move and was no longer able to take to free dog day care to get his energy out. He had to be left during the day in a crate and Denver could not tolerate that.  
 
Then we adopted him out again to a wonderful home with 4 young kids all under the age of 10.  Denver did just fine with all the kids, no issues there.  But all that activity, noise, etc. seemed to cause stress and anxiety for Denver.  According to the Mom, he was anxious and usually didn’t want to really stay where all the kids were.  He was great during the day when he and the other dog were just there or just the adults were there but they could tell he could not relax when there was so much activity going on in the home.  They feared they were causing him more harm than good.  So Denver is again back with us.
 
Here what they said about Denver in this home:
He is very good riding in the car and on a leash.  Denver is a good watchdog and will bark when someone approaches the door.  He enjoys running and likes to chase other dogs and be chased by friends. Denver will chase cats but doesn’t attack them.  He’s a great dog but be warned:  he will get stuff off the counters if he can reach it!! And he will get things out of your sink, dishes, thawing meat, cups, etc.
Denver is a very social, sweet, fun-loving active dog. He loves walking, hiking, swimming, dog parks and of course belly rubs and coach cuddling. He seems to do just fine with other dogs, cats and children. Now sometimes he doesn't like to share his toys with other dogs so will need to watch that.

Denver is a super dog but he just doesn't like being crated for a long period of time - that is most of the day and all night. He will do best having a yard to run around and play in during the day or for a good part of the day (or dog day care) and then can be crated at night for sleeping. He is active and will need to get that energy out of him. He is too big and active for an apartment.  Denver’s next home will be a calmer home with either no or adult children.  He will require a fenced in yard.  

Denver is up to date on his vet care, neutered,
heartworm negative and is microchipped. He is on heartworm and flea/tick prevention. Thank goodness dogs are so adaptive and live in the moment - this will help Denver as he adjusts to his new situation and then to another new home!

All HSWA dogs are either at our Dog Adoption Facility or in foster homes. All dogs require an appointment to meet.  Please call us at 205-554-0011 or email humaneswa@yahoo.com to request an appointment to see the dog/puppy and to check availability.

Visit us on Facebook! www.facebook.com/humaneswa

Our adoption fee is $75.  Read more information on our adoption process at www.humanesocietyofwa.org/howtoadopt.html.  Then, if you feel your home might be the right forever home and you would like to adopt a dog, submit an online adoption application. The online applications may not work on mobile devices. If the online application does not work on your device, look to the right side of the forms page for a downloadable .PDF copy of the application.

Puppies/Dogs that are not available for adoption due to vetting not being complete can be reserved with an approved application and a non refundable $50 deposit. This deposit is applied to your adoption fee and the remaining $125 is due at pick up.

Wags and Whiskers is an all-volunteer rescue. We also have full-time jobs and Families. We will try to answer all questions and applications in a timely manner. Please be patient and bear with us . Do not contact Parkway Animal Hospital as they are a vet clinic and can not answer questions on behalf of Wags and Whiskers. All questions and comments must go directly through the rescue. animal.description:
JASPER HAS BEEN ADOPTED!!!

****Email us for a video of Jasper  info@sosr.ca  ****
****Jasper is being fostered in Newmarket****

JASPER is a very lovely 5 year old sable Sheltie boy who needs a new home due to owner's personal circumstances.  

Jasper is timid but once he gets used to people,  he's very affectionate...but not a cuddler....licks and wants to be petted in the chest area....  however it takes time and patience to have him trust people. Jasper startles easily at sudden noises or movements  – but he is also curious and wants to see what made the noise or movement.  He is a quick learner and is already used to the noises made by our washer, dryer, kettle, coffee maker and printer. He will need  work on continuing his socialization.  He needs a home with no other pets. 
 
Jasper is very playful with stuffed squeaky toys and balls and likes to play outside in the foster home's yard.  Jasper is becoming more comfortable on walks but is reactive to noises and dogs that he meets.  He will need someone who can work on this or have a good sized yard where he would get most of his exercise.
.
He is reliably housetrained and is non-destructive in the house, but he is also crate trained.....just doesn't need it at this point.

Jasper is a smart boy and is now learning basic commands like sit, come with his foster mom.  He needs someone who is experienced with fearful dogs and who has the time, patience and knowledge  to work on this.

This boy has the making of a great companion to the right family who has experience with fearful dogs and is willing to work with him and will accept his idiosyncrasies.

Jasper fun facts....

1)  Jasper loves “foot rubs” – not the kind where you rub his feet with your hands – but the kind where you rub him all over with your feet;

2)  Jasper loves to chase sunbeams and prisms and the movement of shadows on the wall.  He will play with his foster dad for 5-10 minutes following the sunbeam from his watch around the room each morning.  If he sees a prism on the wall, he watches the movement – and the same with the movement of shadows on the wall....and  has such a look of wonderment as he does it!

3)  Jasper isn’t afraid of thunder.  He will bark when he hears the noise, but he is not cowering in the bathtub.  In fact, he goes looking for the source of the noise.

4) Jasper snores.  Not loud in your face snoring – just audible happy snuffley snoring.

*****PLEASE NOTE THAT DUE TO COVID 19 WE ARE NOT CURRENTLY CONSIDERING CROSS BORDER ADOPTIONS.
***********************************************************

*****If you have a securely fenced yard and are interested in adopting JASPER or any of our dogs, the first step is to complete an Adoption Application at www.sosr.ca/apply-to-adopt so that we can determine whether you and your family are a good match for one of the dogs. If we have a possible match, you would then have a telephone interview, speak to the foster mom, have a home visit by one of our volunteers and vet reference check.

animal.description:
Hi there, I’m glad to see you checking out my page! I’m Beckham Barkley and it’s great to meet you. I’m looking for a new family to call my own! Could it be you?

Here’s my stats:
Possible Breed:  Chihuahua Shih Tzu Mix
Gender:  Male
Colors:  Black and White
Age:  9 years young
Weight:  10 pounds

Now for the good stuff!-

So I am really a striking dog. My color and my hair make me unique! My foster mom says that I may be a little dog but I have a BIG personality (as do most Chihuahuas). 

Hey, know what I really love? Laps! I love to sit on laps so if you are looking for a companion to hang out with you and, be close to you, I'm your guy!   I love to get petted too.  If I see a hand dangling like they want to pet, I'll run up and ask for my share of pets.  I love, love, love attention!

I do need to tell you that I can be possessive of my food bowl. Ya know, living without enough food before I got to Lone Star, can make a fellow worry. So it would be best if I live in a house without little kids because they wouldn't really understand to stay back when I'm eating. And I would never want to get carried away and nip a little kid. So best that I live with teenagers or adults! 

When I came to LS, I had mange but it's been under control for a long time. If I have a flair up, there's a bit of medication I can take to get back on track. Otherwise, I'm healthy.

Start the process of adopting me or one of the other pups by filling out the application found at www.shihtzu-rescue.com.

PS. I've had ALL my vetting, and oh boy, it was a lot. Here's what I had done..
Distemper/Parvo shots - TWICE (Foster Mom said we have to have two so that we are protected from these horrible viruses. One doesn't cut it.)
Bordetella shots - ALSO TWICE. 
Spay/Neuter, of course.
A fecal exam so I don't have any bad worms.
A heartworm test.
BLOODWORK to make sure my liver and kidneys are working well, because you know, we doggies often have issues in the liver and kidneys.
A DENTAL exam AND cleaning if I needed it- yep, all my toofies are checked so they can be in tip top shape
See, that's a LOT. Ask your vet - that's a LOT.

You can apply to adopt this adorable little fluff at www.shihtzu-rescue.com.  This adorable little fluff has been spayed or neutered, is up to date on all vaccinations and heartworm negative.

Hi!  My name's Cindy Lou!  I'm a friendly pup who's looking for a new best friend.  Will YOU be my forever friend??

I was found as a stray and brought to the shelter.  I don't know what happened to my former family, but I sure do miss them!  Hopefully my new family will be the one I'm meant to be with forever and ever.

I'm already up to date on vaccinations, spayed, and I also have a microchip!  If you think I'm the girl for you please stop by the shelter and spend some time getting to know me!  I'll be excited to meet you!

animal.description: Hi! My name is Danica Patrick like the female NASCAR driver. I suffered a catastrophic injury to my back legs on December 10, 2019, when I was hit by a truck on 40 Highway.  Luckily for me, good samaritans pulled me from the highway and brought me to the vet clinic, that was conveniently across the street, where it was determined I suffered a break to my spine. The clinic tried to find out where I came from and if anyone was missing me, but no such luck. The Doctor and Technicians here take REALLY good care of me. They are letting me heal and getting me fitted for a wheelchair.  I am doing awesome in the borrowed wheelchair. True to my name I like to go FAST!! I am still young and full of spunk. I like to be very vocal especially when I know I am about to get fed or go in my wheelchair. I do get along great with other dogs. I have mastered how to drag myself around when I am not in a wheelchair. I am considered special needs, so I know I am not for everyone, but if you are the right person to adopt me I will fill your heart with lots of love!

animal.description:
Poor Jughead! He got that name because something plastic like a milk jug was stuck on his head and he couldn't remove it! He roamed a neighborhood for quite a while like that because no one could catch him. Some people in the neighborhood finally called us about him. A few of our amazing volunteers went into action and finally caught him, removed the jug, and took him to the shelter. He was so scared when he arrived that he wouldn't even make eye contact with anyone, and it was virtually impossible to put a leash on him.

Volunteers have spent a lot of time with him to help with his socialization, and he is definitely more at ease around people he knows. He is currently undergoing leash training with volunteers. 

Jughead loves other dogs and children.  He is really a sweet and very handsome boy, and we are thrilled with the progress he is making. We're sure he'll get the hang of the leash soon! Jughead's date of birth is 3/2/2019 and he weighs about 72 pounds.

We had a DNA test done on Jughead and we found out he is 50% Great Pyrenees, 25% American Staffordshire Terrier, 12.5% Akita, and 12.5% Sporting/Guard Dog Breed Groups.

You can submit an adoption application for this sweet boy at http://www.fayettefcar.com/applicationform, where you can also review FCAR’s adoption requirements.

All FCAR adoptable dogs have been spayed or neutered, are current on all vaccines, on flea/tick and heartworm prevention, microchipped, and come with a 30-day pet health guarantee. The adoption fee is $95 with an approved application. A fenced yard is required for Jughead.

animal.description: Susie is a beautiful brindle girl who was picked up as a stray in northern Kentucky. She arrived at the vet clinic and all it took was a a couple of days and the wonderful staff showing her so much love and giving her a warm medicated bath to bring her out of her shell. She is incredibly sweet and and she is eating great! She will receive all of her needed vetting then she will need a foster home to relax in so we can get to know her better and help her find her perfect home. 1/31: Susie has started on her pre-treatment medications and will be moving to her Minnesota foster home very soon!3/2: Susie arrived at her Minnesota foster home a couple of weeks ago and has gotten pretty comfy. It did take her a little bit to adjust to the much colder temperatures and all of the snow on the ground but she has finally decided that it's not so bad. Susie is getting the royal treatment in her foster home including getting a pawdicure and getting medicated baths for her dry/itchy skin, which she has really started to love. She will be seeing the vet on Friday to ensure that she is healthy enough to start heartworm treatment as she was pretty thin when she joined us. Her foster mom & dad have been working with her on crate training and she is doing great!! She also has a new best friend in her foster furbrother Sarge.4/4 UPDATE: Susie is undergoing heartworm treatment and is doing great! She is on her second round of treatment and after a few weeks of crate and couch rest she will be all ready to be spayed and have some needed dental work.6/9/20: Susie is about 8 weeks post heartworm treatment and we will be getting her retested very soon to see if she can be cleared for spay and dental surgery. 8/17/20: We are getting closer to the big day to retest Susie after her heartworm treatment. She is doing well in her foster home and will be ready for adoption very soon!!11/22/20: Susie had her heartworm recheck and she was cleared for surgery! She will be spayed and get her needed dental work done on December 8th.
