*We are closed to the public for viewing. Please email adoptions@pawstinleypark.org if you are interested in adopting Holly, please fill out an application on our website.


Holly is a 2-1/2-year-old mixed breed (our best guess is Shar Pei/Shepherd) looking for her true love!  Holly came to us over 10 months ago with her 4 beautiful puppies.  She has been very scared and doesn’t seem to be used to people very much.  With lots of time and patience, Holly has learned to trust our volunteers and will stick by your side when she is comfortable with you.  This mama dog has the saddest eyes and we know she just wants to be loved.  Holly is looking for a quiet and patient home that will help her become the confident dog we know she can be!
Toys make Holly very happy, she can never have enough of them!

If you are interested in meeting this pet, please visit our website to check on their current availability: http://www.pawstinleypark.org.. Adoptions are limited to 50 miles from the shelter. We do not ship animals. Adoption fees for dogs are $125-$275 based on age. While we do our best, we cannot make guarantees on breed, exact age and house training of our dogs. Peoples Animal Welfare Society (P.A.W.S.) of Tinley Park, IL is a no-kill non-profit 501(c) (3) organization.

animal.description:
"BE SURE TO WATCH MY VIDEO!" 

Date of birth:  11/2017

12/13/2020: Abe is a friendly and playful Lab mix!  He’s acts like a big puppy.   He is a fun-lovin', treat-catchin' bundle of energy! Abe would literally jump for joy to have his own human playmate tossing him toys or treats in the back yard, or popcorn in the living room. And he'd be happy to work on some treat motivated training with his new person. We think Abe would love agility training and be great at it.  He’s also a big fan of plush toys, chew toys and nylabones.  

• Abe is quite vocal and would not be suited for apartment/townhouse living.  

• Because of his high activity level, he'd really do best with a fenced yard.  He needs an active person to keep him busy and take him for long walks or runs.

• He's very bright and a fast learner! He know basic obedience and would love to learn more.

• Once you wear him out, he's loving and he likes to cuddle!

• Abe needs a home without young kids. He's got too much energy and not enough manners or regard for personal space right now! He'd be fine with teenagers who are used to an active and very physical dog, and enjoy that type of play.  With more training and lots of exercise in his new home, he'd probably be fine with young kids eventually. 

• Abe is a bit choosy with his dog friends.  He likes some dogs and has played out in the yard with dogs, but we've had problems with it escalating into a fight.  We think it may be best for Abe to not live with other dogs.

• Abe is 3 years old and weighs 65 lbs. He has a beautiful B&W coat. When he came to us he was a stray and he had a broken foot that had healed on its own, but crookedly. But it doesn’t slow him down one bit!  

• Abe has been neutered, vaccinated, microchipped and tested for heart worms. He's a sweetie and a lot of fun!

MORE ON ADOPTING OUR DOGS... 

> COVID-19 UPDATE: PLEASE SUBMIT AN ONLINE ADOPTION APPLICATION AND A MEMBER OF OUR ADOPTIONS TEAM WILL REACH OUT TO YOU. Please visit our web site at HSGKC.ORG for an adoption application, our current COVID-19 adoption protocol, and other adoption info.  

> If you decide you'd like to adopt one of the pets you meet, we reserve the pet for you but we generally don't send the pet home with you that day. We’ll instead schedule a pick up date and time that’s convenient for you.   

> Our goal is to send you home with a healthy pet and any information and support you may need to help your new pet adjust to his or her new home.  All of our dogs & puppies have been spayed or neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, treated for fleas & ticks, tested for heartworms (7 mo. and over), and are on monthly heartworm preventative. Puppies who are too young to receive all the necessary puppy boosters and/or first rabies shot may be brought back to us for those vaccines at no extra charge. You will also receive a leash, collar, coupons for pet supplies and services, toys, and educational materials. And we'll give your dog a bath before he or she goes home! 

> Please note that we prefer and may require a fenced yard for many of our dogs.  Exceptions are made on an individual basis depending on the dog's needs, the person's dog experience, the dog's and person's activity levels, home environment and other factors. 

Thank you for searching for a shelter pet!

Dog Adoption Contact Info:

Phone: 913.596.1000 ext. 113

animal.description:
Greta is a 1.5 year old pittie mix. She was found as a stray on the side of the road, at night, sick with parvo. She beat it, though - she is one strong little girl! 

Greta is VERY shy around new people, especially men. But once she warms up to you, then you are friends for good! Greta LOVES playing with the other dogs in her foster home. She can play hard, but settle down and cuddle, too. She is looking for a home that understands she is shy in the beginning. Another dog really helps bring her out of her shell. Therefore, a home with another dog and a fenced yard to play in is a must to make her feel right at home!

A fenced yard, another playful dog, and a female adult human in the home are all required for Greta's forever home. She has been adopted and returned once due to her extreme fear of men. She has been in an experienced foster home for over eight months now. She still runs from her foster dad sometimes. Greta needs an experienced owner with time and patience to continue working on building her confidence. 

If you have questions or would like to speak with Greta's foster mom, please email your contact info to cohkcvolunteer@gmail.com and she will give you a call. Thanks!

$200 Adoption fee includes spay, dewormer, vaccinations, rabies tag, microchip, heartworm test and heartworm/flea/tick prevention.

Fill out an application at www.chainofhopekc.org/adopt

**Local Adoptions Only- Kansas City**
**Currently in Foster Home**

animal.description:
‘CLASSIC CARTOON’ THEMED MOMMA:  6 years old / 49 lbs.  

Hi, I’m Betty Boop! I came to Mostly Mutts very pregnant & heartworm positive, so I’m super grateful to have been rescued. My puppies have found their furever homes, & now it’s my turn to find my home & live the good life!  I’ve completed my heartworm treatment and am healthy now!

• OTHER DOGS/CATS/KIDS: I’ve liked most of the dogs that I met at Mostly Mutts & in my foster homes.  So, if you have a dog, let’s meet & see if we’ll be good play pals as I do enjoy playing with other dogs and I sleep with another dog in a comfy dog bed in my foster home. Sometimes I’m nervous around dogs at first, so a proper outdoor introduction is key / No kitty cats, I chased the kitty in my foster home in a playful way, but I’m just too much dog for a cat / I met a nice 10-year-old boy & a girl slightly younger at Mostly Mutts & did well with them, so calm kids around age 10 (or slightly younger) in my new home could be fun, let’s meet!  I also lived with a 10 yr. old boy who became my best friend. 

• PERSONALITY/ENERGY LEVEL: I’m a sweet, cuddly, playful, active & very friendly tail wagger who will give my paws to my people & do a happy little dance with them – so cute! I want to be with my people a lot & wouldn’t do well if you were gone all day for work. So, I will be happiest in a home with a stay/work from home family member who wants to spend lots of time with their dog. I do have some anxiety & bark if left too much, so an apartment is not a good fit for me (I’m on some meds for anxiety, see below). However, I am dealing better with this, but just give me some time to adjust to a new home. Also, a home with a secure, tall fence would be best for me so that I have plenty of running space to work off some energy / My energy level is 5-7+ & I like playing with my people.

• SKILLS/CRATE/POTTY: I’m very smart & a proud graduate of the Mostly Mutts University training program. I’ve mastered the ‘sit’, ‘stay’, ‘down’, ‘come’, ‘drop it’, ‘leave it’ & ‘place’ commands.  I also use proper door etiquette & have good leash manners as well as accept nice strangers without jumping. I have issues with people that enter my home so I need to meet new people outdoors for the greatest success. I also have issues with people that are dressed in all dark color clothing. They scare me & this makes me want to protect my people. My foster family is teaching me that I’m ok when seeing people in dark clothing. You will need to continue to watch this with me. I ride well in the car so you can take me places with you! / I do not like being in my crate & have barked for long periods of time when in a crate or behind a gate in my temp foster home, as I really just like being with my people. In my current foster home, I am doing very well sleeping at night on a large comfy dog bed in their bedroom / I’m doing great with my potty manners on a good schedule & even use the doggy door to go outside when I need to potty!

• LIKES/DISLIKES:  I love squeaky toys, balls, stuffed toys, Nyla bones & antlers. I love my daily walks & am a fantastic jogging and hiking buddy.  My favorite place to hang out is with my people, & I love all the cuddles that come my way / I don’t like being in water, & people dressed in dark clothing make me very nervous. In my former home, I bit a person’s ankle who was dressed in dark clothing. I also don’t like being restrained by the vet & I would not be happy if I didn’t get the attention & love on which I thrive. 

• MEDICAL:  I am on some anxiety medications & may be able to be weaned off those once that I’m settled into my new home.  Time will tell. I’m current on vaccinations, micro-chipped & spayed.  

I’m looking for a family to make me a cherished family member!  My adoption fee is $299.00, & I’m in Kennesaw, Ga.

animal.description:
Meet Phoebe! She was an owner surrender with her brother Chandler to a local high kill shelter before finding their way to the safety of Maxx & Me. She is a lab/pit mix and is about 11 months old and 40 pounds. She did great in boarding and plays nicely with others and ready for his happily ever after! She is so happy and silly! She needs a 6' fenced in yard, an active home, and a dog buddy that's ready for playful shenanigans!! Phoebe is exuberant and energetic and love to JUMP! She would probably really enjoy agility courses, long runs, hikes, and adventures of all sorts. This girl is just full of FUN!! She is great with older kids, hasn't been around toddlers.
Applications can be found @ maxxandme.org
Phoebe is spayed, up to date on vaccines, and microchipped. Her adoption donation is only $250!
Maxx & Me is an all volunteer, all foster home rescue and do not have a shelter. Please allow at least 48 hours for applications to be processed (missing information may slow the process, so please take your time and be thoughtful in your answers). All dogs posted are available (so no need to ask). We place dogs based on best home for each dog and not order of applications received. Email us at maxxandmerescue@gmail.com for updates and questions. Thank you for choosing rescue.

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Kiwi!  I love kisses, playing tug of war, snuggling, and taking long naps in my humans lap (although i'll nap in my crate if a human lap isn't available).   

I also love playing with toys, any toys, all toys, yay toys!  My  favorite thing in the whole world is car rides, though!  It doesn't matter where we're going, as long as I can ride in the car with you!   

I am crate trained and house trained! I'd do best without small children because I have a big puppy personality so I'm  still learning to keep all 4 paws on the ground when I get too excited. Even though I am a very hyper puppy, that also means I am a great running buddy! 

I need a little help with leash manners, but trust me I'll run with you as long as you want if you'll have some patience!! I've been in rescue since I was a little puppy. 

I was found in the middle of the street with my brother, and I was so sick and unhealthy that I had almost no hair! I grew up with a lot of anxiety because of this but in my 3 years in rescue I've gotten a lot of training to help with my anxiety.

 I would be best in a single dog home, but I promise to do my ABSOLUTE BEST to be on my best behavior if you have some patience and love for me!  I can't wait to meet my forever family, who I will love more than ANYTHING!!

Please give me a chance to show you that I can be the best companion ever! Will you give me a shot?? 

If you are interested, please call or text my Aunt Cindy at 713 306-8045 or email her at cfitzger2019@yahoo.com. My adoption fee include all my shots, spay, microchip and transport. My adoption fee is $450

Thank you for listening to my story!

animal.description:
Friends to the Forlorn
Adopt-a-BullBreed: Pit Bull Terrier
Gender: Female
Estimated Date of Birth: December 12, 2017
Size: 66 lbs
Location: Talking Rock, GA

RESCUING CEELY

Ceely, formerly known as Citrine, ended up at Cherokee County Animal Control where she was labeled "rescue only." She was found as a stray with a rope around her neck. We don't know much about her past, but it was obvious it was not a good one. She appeared to be healthy aside from some skin issues (Demodex). Ceely passed temperament testing, but the shelter staff said she appeared to be a bit fearful of men, was more confident outside, and was more shy indoors. She spent over a month at Animal Control before she got her freedom ride on December 12, 2019.

ABOUT CEELY

Ceely is now enjoying that foster life and on the hunt for her forever family. She is fully vetted, crate-trained and housebroken. She loves being outside, going for walks, playing in the creek, and chasing balls. She also loves cuddling on the sofa with her doggie friends or in the recliner with her foster mom. She currently has two doggie foster-siblings (a male and a female) and she has the most adorable play-bows and hops when playing with them in the yard. She's even good with the horses on the property! Ceely is still a bit nervous around strangers and tends to bark when she's afraid. Her foster family is working on this and she is showing lots of improvement. With slow, proper introductions, Ceely warms up to people and will lick their hands. She takes treats gently, is extremely sweet, and loves a good belly rub. She is learning to enjoy being a much loved member of a family. It is apparent that humans were previously unkind to her, so Ceely is looking for a forever family that will give her the some time to adjust and continue learning that not all people are cruel. She is a wonderful girl who would do well in a home with another dog and even horses! She is probably not suited for a home with cats as she seems to be overly interested in her foster family's barn cats.

Photo Album of Ceely: https://www.facebook.com/pg/FriendsToTheForlornPitbullRescue/photos/?tab=album&album_id=2872985706092910

Our adoption fee is $300. All dogs are current on vaccinations, spayed or neutered, micro-chipped, on heartworm prevention, and are fed top of the line grain-free food.www.savingpitbulls.org

animal.description:
Are you looking to have your dog skills and experience challenged? Do you have the patience of a saint? Then Mighty is ready to test you. Seriously, he’s an 8.6 magnitude earthquake in a city without building codes. He is a rainstorm on a herd of Gremlins, after midnight… with a plate of food.  For example:

1.	Speaking of rainstorms – he hates them. As well as fireworks. Just about any loud, new, or odd noise scares him. He is even afraid of his farts.
2.	He has the leash manners like some of those shoppers on Black Friday. You know, where the store is giving away an item to the first 200 guests. He just gets so excited sometimes he feels the need to jump up and grab the leash and walk himself.
3.	Mighty has an allergy or several. No chicken for sure and probably no other poultry. Grains make him itchy, and sometimes he gets pink.
4.	He’s one of those “blocky headed” dogs… pit balls, pot bois, pibbles, poblanos, whatever.
5.	He’s nervous with new people, and he warms up to women quicker than men. Do you know that site with all the dogs who love the UPS guy? Mighty will not likely be making an appearance on that site.

Here are some things we also know about Mighty. He completely loves his people. Once you’re in, you’re in for life. He likes to make new people friends, too, and that takes some time and treats… and those are treats without caramel color, because you know, the allergies. He loves attention, training, and showing his set of learned skills. He likes drinking from the hose, being outside with his people, and helping with yard work. If you have sticks, he’ll chew them. If you’re pulling weeds, he’ll shake them and spit them out…mostly. 

We’ve loved this guy from the moment we saw him tied to a tree with a note stating, “My name is Mighty, …just tell me it’s OK Needs a good home and lots of love” We’ve come a long way from where he wouldn’t go near the car, wouldn’t go up or down the stairs, and only went outside to do his business. He now, cannot wait for the next car ride and uses the stairs like Rocky. (Except for the basement stairs, they’re still scary.) We’re not going to lie though; his forever home is one in a million. His new home will require experience, management, smarts, time and dedication. 

As they say, nothing worthwhile comes easy and nothing that comes easy is worthwhile. Mighty is a sweet, playful, loving dog, and is very loyal in his devotion to his people.  He has quite a few quirks, but hey, who doesn’t? He has a long life ahead of him, and deserves an active, loving home that will always tell him, it’s OK.

animal.description: I'm Midnight. My previous owners used to breed me. Thankfully some nice people rescued me when my owners abandoned me in a closed up house with no food or water. I had been in that hot house far longer than I wish to talk about. When they came to get me I was so scared. It took the nice lady trying to help me two whole hot dogs and a bottle of water to gain my trust. Now I smile and show my pretty teeth at her when I see her. I am still fearful of new people. It takes me just a bit to warm up to them. Once I do, I'm a lover. Some neighbors told my rescuers that I used to have human brothers and sisters living with me and that I like them. I've been around a pretty rowdy three year old human boy for a bit. He's my friend. I'm not sure how I'd be around cats as I haven't been around any. I like other dogs but they need to be smaller than me. I'd really like to find my forever home. Can you help me with that?

animal.description:
Harley is a seven-year-old American Eskimo female, who came to rescue from a puppy mill in Ohio. This girl is the sweetest, purest soul and it shows in her eyes as she looks at you. No bad bone in her body. She is steadily gaining confidence in herself and showing an inclination towards play while outside. She knows basic commands-sit and down, but readily offers her paw and will give kisses. It does take time for her to open up, but once she does, she is a sweetheart. 
She is not yet interested in toys, but will chew on buffalo horns and deer antlers, loves treats, and just wants to please.
She needs work on her leash training and has figured out how to get collars off, so a home with a fenced yard is MANDATORY. No apartment life for her. 
Harley is house-trained and crate-trained and is food motivated. 
She needs a quiet home with very understanding and calm people that will respect her space and trusting curve.
She would not do well in a house with children due to their activity levels.

SHE GETS CAR SICK AND IS A FLIGHT RISK....so adoptions have to be within 2 to 3 hours of Cincinnati for her safety.

animal.description:
Bella is a beautiful 3-year old female Pit Bull Terrier mix who was surrendered by her owner on February 7, 2019.

Bella has a white short smooth coat with patches of black on her right side and hind quarters, a long tail, and an adorable face with a black button nose, short semi-erect ears, and expressive eyes that beg for attention. 

This little sweetheart has an affectionate personality. When Bella first came to our shelter (nearly a year ago now), she was rather reserved and took awhile to warm up to new people.  These days Bella is wiggling all over at the front of her kennel in anticipation of attention or a w-a-l-k :)  Her current kennel is one of our more open access ones with chain-link fencing on both sides so that she can interact with her neighbors (usually younger dogs and puppies), and Bella is very nice to them.

Her previous owner told us that Bella has been kept indoors and is housebroken. She knows several basic commands (sit, stay, shake, and roll over).  Bella has no known behavioral issues.

Bella has an allergy to fleas and must be kept on a good-quality flea treatment to keep her comfortable and also to prevent hair loss.  

Bella weighed 46.2 lbs on intake in February 2019 and was already spayed.  She appears to have gained a few pounds since then thanks to the gourmet meals our kennel techs serve up each day :)

Bella spent approximately two months in a foster home this past summer.  She was returned in mid-September 2019 because her foster family moved and there was an unfortunate incident with a door being chewed .. Bella prefers to take the 'Fifth Amendment' and doesn't really want to elaborate about the details :( 

These updated photos of Bella were taken on the afternoon of December 24, 2019 as she enjoyed a nice walk in the sunshine with one of our volunteers.  Bella is even more beautiful these days and looked especially festive in her bright red jester's collar.

This little sweetheart has an affectionate disposition and a rather reserved personality. Bella loves attention but doesn't like to be approached suddenly or to rush into a relationship.

Her previous owner told us that Bella has been kept indoors and is housebroken. She knows several basic commands (sit, stay, shake, and roll over). Bella has no known behavioral issues.

Bella has an allergy to fleas.

Bella weighs 46.2 lbs and has already been spayed.

Please note that these "first photos" of Bella were taken on February 9, 2019.  We took updated glamour photos on December 24, 2019, and she is looking even more beautiful these days.

animal.description:
My name is Bocce (pronounced Botchy – yes, I just had to be different).  I am an approximately 6 years old extremely handsome Gordon Setter mix.  You can see my photos and if I have to say so myself, they just don’t do me justice.  To get the basics out of the way – I am neutered and up to date on my vaccinations.  I’ve lived in a kennel situation for quite awhile, so my house training might need a little work.  I’m a good sized boy – I weigh about 70 pounds.  

So, first - I don't do well with cats.  I have a super high prey drive and would be best as the only dog - at least to begin with.  

I am being fostered by Companion Golden Retriever rescue in Utah.  Not sure why I’ve been here this long.  You don’t see many of me in rescue in this part of the country – so, come on people.  

Unfortunately, I found myself in rescue when I got a little possessive of the lady of the house and tangled a little with the resident dog.  So, instead of working through it, they decided I was not the dog for them.  Their loss because I am the total favorite of some of the volunteers and they are super surprised that I am still not adopted (me too!).  They wonder if it’s because when I first meet people, well…  I get a little excited (ok, a lot excited)!  But, come’on – setter people KNOW us setters – we’re an exuberant breed.  

I’ve been through the Canine Good Citizen (CGC) class a couple times.  I still haven’t passed – so, I get a little distracted (I heard rumors of being accused of being the class clown – I don’t see the problem, do you?).  That is really just a part of my charming personality.  By the way, try having these classes outside where BIRDS fly over?  Uh – setter!!!  

I like routine and structure and would do very well with someone that will set boundaries for me.  I’m living in the rescue’s kennel facility and while I get to get out and play a lot and spend time with the rescue’s trainer, I do need more socialization that I can get here.  If you adopt me and work with me, I will be such a wonderful friend and companion.  I do walk quite well on the leash, but I can be easily distracted – uh, yoohoo –  setter, birdy guy!  But, just think of the compliments you’ll get as you walk or run with me.  

I love these people, but I would really like my own home and frankly – it’s way past time.  I would do best in a home probably without kids as I’m a big boy and my exuberance could easily knock little kids over - then they cry and it’s just a big mess.  Let’s avoid that.  I do need a secure yard and preferably someone that understands my breed and my needs; and, I should probably either be an only dog, or live with a pretty laid back or more submissive dog as I can be pretty possessive of my toys and food.  People call because I’m so handsome, but it’s not always a match.   

So, if you think you would be interested in adopting me, you can email Deb at utgoldentails.@cs.com, Companion Golden Retriever Rescue in West Jordan, Utah; or, contact Kelley at 208-869-4065 or email at k40moore@cableone.net.  You won’t be sorry!

animal.description:
Special needs
Munchkin is diabetic and has Cushings. She is 10 years old,  She requires an adopter who has knowledge and the financial resources to manage diabetes shots, specialized diet, glucose and ketone testing and ketoacidosis, and giving fluids if needed. She also needs daily supplements..  Please do not apply if you have no experience or financial means to care for her.  She is not a science experiment.  We realize she has a very narrow likelihood of finding the right fit.  Please consider supporting her care, we really would be grateful.

That being said, Munchkin is an amazing dog with a sweet personality.  She is the perfect companion for people and other pets.  She has great house manners and a happy disposition.  Munchkin loves to take walks and romp in the yard, bark at squirrels an play with foster dog friends.  Munchkin in Type 1 diabetic and does require a skilled adopter who has the resources and the know how to manage her diabetes and Cushings .  If that is you, please contact us on this website or you can email us at RescueTailsAnimalWelfare@gmail.com.  We do work full time and will make every effort to repond to you in 48 hours or less.

We do require an approved adoption application before we will schedule a required home visit and meet and greet.  We only adopt within in the local Chicago  area.  Thank you!

This gorgeous brindle boy is Oso (Porter). He was hit by a car and had a right humeral fracture and bilateral elbow dysplasia. After Oso's surgery he has adjusted very well and actually seems happier than before since he is no longer struggling with pain!! He is now with us at the Akita Ranch and has quickly become a staff favorite!! He is friendly and bubbly as can be... LOVES affection, to play with you, splashing in his pool, going for walks, and smiling at all times. Even though he only has 3 legs he is just as physically capable as any of our Akita's. Once you meet Oso (Porter) you will never be the same!! Email: apassionforpaws@gmail.com for adoption information Visit Akita Ranch 28930 Ellis Ave, Romoland, CA, Open 10-5 daily BY APPOINTMENT ONLY. animal.description: Meet this handsome boy, Johnny Cash! This oversized gentle giant is looking for a home with mostly carpet, no stairs, or smaller animals. Johnny needs a family that will be able to support him as he gets older and using hip lifters may be in his future, and at 140+ pounds that is something to consider. He is vert playful (loves playing fetch) and is mostly good on leash but he is a very strong boy and may pull (could use a bit of a leash manners refresher). This beautiful soul wants nothing more than to have someone to curl up on the couch with and be loved for the rest of his life.

Well look no further....Hi!! My name is Charlie!! 

Not sure if you saw my story, but I was rescued by these nice people here from a shelter.  I was very emaciated ... but I am now happy and healthy and looking for my forever home where I can be spoiled and loved like I deserved my entire life... and looking forward to putting the past behind me.
I am a 3 year old sweet boy that is looking for someone that will teach me that living in a house is pretty darn awesome!  Even though I was treated poorly in my past.. I hold no grudges.... I just love people!! and I just LOVE to play with my toys!! 
 I would be best as an only pet, as I was not socialized with other animals much. 
I would love to go for walks or play in the yard with you... and then curl up on a nice comfy dog bed or maybe even next to you on the couch after! 
If you think I could be the boy for you... please fill out an adoption application at:
               www.dawghous.com
Thank you
Love Charlie
(video was taken beginning of November before I was all better... but shows how much I love my toys and what a fun boy I am!!! )

animal.description:
Meet Shelly
Shelly is a gorgeous girl who was dropped off at Animal Control. We pulled Shelly as soon as we learned she was going to be euthanized to make room for more dogs. Shelly arrived to the safety of our shelter on July 5, 2019. 
Shelly will steal your heart. She has a beautiful face, gorgeous coloring and her eyes plead for your attention. Shelly is a 3.6 three-year-old Staffordshire/Bulldog mix. She is solidly built with a big gorgeous block head and she’s sleekly muscled. She weighs 57 pounds. It looks as if Shelly has been bred for her puppies and then tossed aside when she was no longer useful. Her face is also covered in scars, which us makes us think that even worse things happened to Shelly in her previous life. But Shelly doesn’t wear the trauma of her former life on her sleeve -- no way! This girl is nothing but kind and gentle to everyone she meets, people and kids, alike. To see her take treats will break your heart. She’s soooo gentle and calm. She lives for attention. However, maybe given how she was treated early on and the situation she came from, Shelly has shown that she doesn’t like other dogs or small animals. She will need to be the only pet in the family. 
Shelly loves walking. She can be a strong walker, but will walk forever if given the chance. She will make for an excellent hiking or running companion. We think Shelly may be house-trained as she won’t soil her kennel, but waits until she can get outside to do her business. She is very smart and it will be important to exercise her mind as well as her body. 
Shelly has had a rough go in life, but she picks herself up and moves on. She has a solid temperament and puts herself out there to be loved and adored. If you’re looking for a young dog with a calm and gentle demeanor and want to open your heart and home to the best doggie companion, come meet our Shelly.  We bet you’ll fall in love with her as we have. 
Shelly is spayed, microchipped and fully vetted.
Call 706-865-4135 for information on additional health services provided as part of the adoption fee.  If interested in one of our puppies or dogs, please submit an application online or at the shelter. Applications can be submitted online at: https://www.charlessmithgallhumanesociety.org/page/dog-adoption-application 
Once an application is submitted online, you will receive an email saying your application has been successfully submitted.  If you don’t receive this email within 24 hours, please check to make sure all application fields were completed or please call our shelter at 706-865-4135. All adopters must complete an approval process which involves a reference check with current/recent vet and a brief home visit if located in the immediate area. We do permit out of state adoptions. Adopters MUST come to the shelter to transport their new family member home. We do not ship nor do we transport them to their new homes. Adoption policies and application procedures are detailed at the shelter website: http://smithgallhumanesociety.org/ under tab All Adoptable Animals.
Charles Smithgall Humane Society (CSHS) is a No kill shelter. Animals in our care remain safe with us until adopted. Resident animals are primarily owner relinquished and also accepted from local Animal Control. The facility usually is operating at capacity with a list of animals waiting for space to open.
Adoption hours are Thurs and Fri 1-4 p.m., Sat 10 a.m.-4 p.m. and Sun 1-4 p.m. Closed Mondays, Tuesdays, and Wednesdays 
Location: 4823 Helen Hwy. 75N, Sautee, GA 30571, Phone: 706-865-4135
Email: smithgallhumanesociety@windstream.net
Our shelter in Sautee GA is located about 3 miles south of the alpine town of Helen in northeast GA.

Henry is an adult male, bully/boxer mix, approximately 75 pounds and 4 years old. He's a short stout guy with a happy, laid-back personality. So don't let the serious face he puts on for the camera fool you, this boy is all body wiggles and tail wags! Henry loves to play with other dogs, male or female! He enjoys treats of all kinds, walks well on a leash and loves to go for car rides. Henry is ready for a family to love him and give him ALL the belly rubs!! 

Adoption fee: $150; includes spay or neuter, vaccinations (dhlpp and rabies), deworming for intestinal parasites and flea treatment. 

Rescue inquiries can be sent to Friendsofbcacga@gmail.com or you can call the shelter directly at 478-445-5514 and leave a voicemail for a call back from the Rescue and Adoption Coordinator.

The Baldwin County Animal Shelter is often operating at capacity, this means that for every dog or cat that comes in, another must leave via rescue or adoption, or risk being euthanized for space.  Multiple dogs and cats come to the shelter EVERY DAY, which means animals must also be moving out at the same rate. Unfortunately, sometimes there are larger adult, "pitbull" or mix-breed dogs that are continually overlooked for their younger or more "adoptable" counterparts. Please consider adopting a new best friend today!

Hi I'm Marley Mae - I've been a Streetdog since I was a little puppy back in 2013 when I wandered up onto a random porch. I was born around Jan 1, 2013, and I've been with a lady for several years, but the adoption didn't work out and now I'm back with my Streetdog friends looking for the perfect forever home for me. I'm a sweet girl, but I also like my personal space and would do well in a home where I am the only pet. I may not be that old yet, but I have some arthritis that sometimes acts up on me and give me an excuse to take extra naps ;) I'm an Australian Shepherd - Cattle Dog mix, full of so much love and companionship left to give. I love to meet new people, I have a favorite pillow and love soft plushy toys I can chew on. I like to spend time outside in the sunshine too. I've been spending some time in boarding, and I'm ready to find a home to do some serious couch surfing for sure! I'd love to meet all of you soon!

animal.description:
Breed: Pit Bull Terrier
Gender: Female
Estimated Date of Birth: March 15, 2016
Size: 65 lbs
Location: Dallas, GA

RESCUING LUX

A lady was giving Lux, formerly known as Beauty, away outside of a Food Depot. One of our friends was able to convince the woman to give him the puppy in order to keep this sweet girl out of the wrong hands. He called us to ask for help and we just so happened to have a foster home opening for a puppy. Lux was adopted, but has recently come back to us and is search for a forever family where she can be the only pet.

ABOUT
LUX

Lux, also known as Little Lux, is a smart and energetic little lady. She loves eating sticks and going for long walks. Her high energy is equally matched by her cuddling obsession. If she's not snuggling on you on the couch all day or deep underneath the sheets, she's in her favorite cave bed!

Lux LOVES new people, and I do mean LOVES new people - adults and children alike! She tries so hard to sit still, but her tail goes 100 mph and she can't decide whether to sit or get her favorite thing - BELLY RUBS! This girl will stop everything for a belly rub. She is working on being less excited when greeting new people, but is still a work in progress. She is very receptive to consistency with training corrections. Being amazingly smart and clever, no crumb will ever go unfound in your home. Lux is a great personal vacuum!

Lux is also emotionally sensitive. If you are sick or sad, she will nudge her way into your arm and lick you to make it all better. To be honest, she loves giving kisses! She is great on the leash as well. In particular, the pronged collar and the easy walk as well, but will require someone willing to keep working on commands. With simple corrections in the beginning of the walk, she falls into the routine of staying behind you and not pulling on the leash. She is very interested in wildlife roaming the neighborhoods and will furiously wag her tail to get their attention. That being said, you say "keep walking" and she obeys. She is crate-trained and housebroken.

Lux's ideal situation would be in a home as the only pet with a private backyard and a 6 foot fence. Little Lux's love knows no bounds. Her eyes will say it all - hook, line, and sinker! She is looking for snuggles, structure, and maybe a piece of ham (she can recognize the decibel level and smell of cheese/ham packing opening from 200 yards away)! This lady is a real gem and is ready to entertain and snuggle anyone that will have her.

Photo Album of Lux: https://www.facebook.com/pg/FriendsToTheForlornPitbullRescue/photos/?tab=album&album_id=2603076549750495

Our adoption fee is $300. All dogs are current on vaccinations, spayed or neutered, micro-chipped, on heartworm prevention, and are fed top of the line grain-free food.

animal.description:
Helloooooo there nice person! I'm Malyshka; who are you? See my head tilt in a questioning manner. You say you're looking for a dog, eh??? That's amazing! Because I am a dog! You say you knew that? That you came here to the rescue group looking for ME? Truly? You saw me on Facebook when your friend shared my link on their page, and said I was a beautiful girl in North Dakota who needed someone JUST LIKE THEM to be totally happy for the rest of her life? Well, isn't that amazing! I guess that means we're going to be best friends FOREVER! And to think it all started when someone clicked that "share" button.  So go ahead now, go fill out the adoption application and come take me home!  I am tired of being abandoned.

--------------------------------------------------- Intake Date: 3 Jan 2020  ---- Adopted: 2/16/2020 -----Returned to Rescue: 6 Jan 2021 ----- Breed: Shepherd x ----- Age: 2 yrs ----- Size: 45 lbs ----- Status: pound expiration, found astray ----- Compatible with: dogs, cat tested well, and children ----- Suitable for: home with fenced yard ----- Medical/Behavioral Needs: none known -----Additional notes: Malyshka is a very smart and eager to please girl.  She knows sit and down.  She takes treats gently and plays wonderfully with dogs of all sizes. She cat tested beautifully and is very responsive to basic commands!  Lots of videos on the rescue's facebook page! This girl is a very nice pup! -------------------------------------------------------- If interested in meeting and potentially adopting please read the adoption requirements and complete the adoption application located at forbellessake.org. Once processed and approved a meet and greet can be scheduled and if a match an adoption can be finalized at that time. FBS standard adoption fee is $175. All canine residents are fully vetted to include spay/neuter, vaccinations, deworming, microchip, and treated for any known medical needs. Breeds cannot be guaranteed. Housetraining is not guaranteed but crate training is worked on with all residents. If a yard is present, a secure physical fence is required.

animal.description:
We will not be showing dogs until Science Based Home restrictions are lifted for non-essential businesses but are reviewing applications for the best fit for each dog.



Belle originally came from rural Missouri where he was pulled just hours before she was going to be euthanized due to their high kill rate. Belle is a bouncy girl with a fun personality. Belle is excited when she first sees you and will dance around in anticipation of your affection. At heart she is a love bug though, and will lean into you for pets and belly rubs. Bell has done very well in a home environment, while crated during the day. Belle is treat motivated, and is taking well to learning her commands. She also enjoys playing fetch, and will bound after the ball in a happy prance. Belle is a dog that is going to shower you with a lot of love, and will be appreciative of the safe, happy home she is provided with. She will return any love and joy she receives into your life 10 fold. For a fulfilling, purposeful life; look no further than this sweet girl.

Application Process

MAPS’s adoption process is designed to help best place dogs with homes that are in the best interest of the dog and their human companions. The adoption process starts with a prescreen review of a Guardian Application. Making decisions about dog placement in adoptive homes is an "art", not a "science", and there will be times when applications will be denied for various reason(s). This is left to the discretion of the MAPS after reviewing relevant information. MAPS reserves the right to make all decisions regarding placement or final disposition of any rescued dog in its care into a foster or adoptive home. There is absolutely no guarantee, made or implied, that any person or persons requesting to adopt a dog being fostered through MAPS, or posted on MAP's web site, will be granted an adoption. After a successful prescreen, including background checks, the applicant(s) are notified that they can visit the dogs and a time slot is made for the dog and applicant interaction. After the interaction we encourage several days of reflection before adopting a pet to help assure this will be a lifetime commitment of love and quality care for the dog. Next we conduct a home/neighborhood visit to the Guardian Applicant's home. If the home visit proves successful the new mom and/or dad of the dog will sign an Adoption Agreement and share a lifetime of love and mindful growth !

Guardianship Application available for download at

http://tinyurl.com/MAPSFiles



MAPS Dog Rescue Mission

Midwest Area Pit Stop, Inc. (MAPS) is a foster home based rescue located in Madison, Wisconsin established in 2005 after being part of the Chicago Illinois based rescue Furry Friends for several years. MAPS focuses on providing a structured, safe calm environment for the dogs in their care that helps them flourish. This structured home environment is complimented by exercise, Positive Reinforcement Deference Training, very high quality dog food in addition to a broad spectrum of proven food supplements including vitamins and supplements. In addition to fostering, MAPS provides sponsorship funds to help with the veterinary expenses and/or Breed DNA testing to save dogs in need of a rescue at the end of their options. MAPS has been active in the community promoting dog safety, how to build a healthy relationship with your dog, and fighting breed discrimination including breed testing of hundreds of dogs since December 2007. MAPS believes that dogs are a central component for people to have a more meaningful and purposeful life. That is, if people are willing to embrace mindfulness in daily living. Dogs help us connect to reality and make life worth living through example and deep bonds. MAPS is not about how many dogs are adopted in the shortest amount of time but rather measures to help insure the dogs that are adopted do not come back for the wrong reasons.

animal.description:
Meet Zoey! 

Zoey is a sweet girl who loves her people! While she does love adults, she is a bit of a mouthy pup still, so Zoey would do best in a home without children. She isn’t a fan of other dogs or cats either, so Zoey would be best as an only dog and the center of attention! Zoey CAN NOT be adopted into a home with another dog or cat. She also NEEDS to go to a home with a yard, so no apartments or townhomes. What she’s really looking for is a guy who will love her unconditionally and loves American bulldogs! Zoey even has a message for you: “I’ve been on all of these apps swiping to try to find Mr. Right...ah but alas no luck yet...I’m still waiting and hoping that my knight in shining armor is out there!” She has a shorter coat because of her American Bulldog mix. She loves to play and definitely loves her walks and runs, but she does enjoy her cuddle time. She weighs around 70 pounds and won’t get any bigger because she’s around four years old. She is completely vaccinated, spayed, and microchipped. Zoey came from rural South Texas around 2 years ago, so she is definitely ready for her new home!! Her adoption fee is $100. 

Go to our website https://redfernanimalrescue.org/ and fill out an application if you are interested! Due to the amount of inquiries we are receiving, we are prioritizing adoption applications at this time. Make sure you’re filling out an adoption application on Red Fern Animal Rescue’s site in Colorado, as we are not a shelter in Tennessee! Please give us 48-72 hours to respond to you!

1/12/20 -  Tiny is coming along.  Poor guy had hookworms on top of everything else.  He just had his 3rd day of treatment and he is perking up quite a bit!  We are sure this is what caused his anemia. He was sleeping a lot but much more alert now! He loves to go outside!  We will get some pics of him walking around.  

Once he is better and blood work is improved, he will have a much needed dental.  Thank you for helping us save this little man! 

1/3/20 -   Tiny was going to be taken to a shelter by his owner when someone stepped in and picked him up and called us.  He was transported to Houston yesterday and saw our vet this morning.   

Some of what he has that we know of are the following:
skin infection,  cataracts and atrophy of the irises, luxating patellas, ear infection, ear mites,  small cyst on head, loose and terribly infected teeth  and he is underweight.  We will know more tomorrow when we get blood and urine results.

3/30/20 - We have found that Harley has recurrent skin issues/allergies. Cytopoint has helped the itch, but his hair gets super oily only a few days after a bath. We are trying different shampoos to see what may work. 

1/27/20 - Well, this is one we in rescue have heard so many times. Girl gets yorkie and he is her baby, girl gets married years later and has human baby, and the four legged baby must go. :( 

Unfortunately for Harley, the date they chose to let him go was Thanksgiving. We have promised Harley that his next Thanksgiving will be full of love, belly rubs, kisses and treats with a family that will never give him up. 

Harley is a sweet boy and sleeps on a pillow next to his foster mom's head. He gets along well with the easy going pups in the house, cuddling with a couple of them from time to time. He tends to be a bit nervous around a lot of activity, so we are looking for a quiet household. 

He is very good about going outside to go to the bathroom and comes right back inside. He goes to the door and looks at his foster mom to let him out. Keep in mind that sometimes they do have accidents and things can vary from home to home so don't expect perfection in the housebreaking department! 

Harley does have some skin issues due to allergies. This was reported to us when he was surrendered. He recently had some issues and responded well to Cytopoint. 

His teeth were a mess when he came to us and a dental was done where he ended up losing 22 teeth. He recovered quickly and eats very well! He is on canned food with some water mixed in. 

Harley's blood work looked very good. He does not seem to have any issues other than allergies ... oh, and he does have luxating patellas which is common in yorkies. Best to keep him from jumping up and down on things. Harley walks up steps to his foster mom's furniture! 

This is a charming little guy with a whole lot of love to share with someone. <3

1/3/20 - BIO COMING SOON!

animal.description:
PLEASE READ CISCO'S FULL PROFILE BEFORE INQUIRING.  WE WILL NOT RESPOND TO APPLICANTS OR INQUIRIES THAT DO NOT READ HIS PROFILE. 

IF YOU ARE LOOKING FOR IMMEDIATE GRATIFICATION, CISCO IS NOT FOR YOU. 

Cisco requires multiple meetings before going into a new home.  His foster mom MUST be able to show and observe the interactions with any potential foster or adopter to teach them how to manage his fears.  

**************************************
If you're interested in adopting me after reading my full profile below, please go to the rescue website and submit the online adoption application by copying and pasting the link below into your web browser. 

http://lowermainlandhumanesociety.org/adoption-application/

A adoption application and home visit is required.  We will not respond to inquiries sent through the Petfinder "ASK ABOUT ME" button. 

Cisco was found abandoned and tied to a bus stop in Surrey.  He was picked up by animal control and ended up in the municipal shelter.  He did not do well there as his fear levels were so high.  He is about 6 years old, 10 lbs..

He was taken out of the shelter by another rescue society and placed in foster care for 3 weeks.  However he did not do well there, as the foster parent didn't understand that Cisco did not want to be forced to interact with humans.  He just wasn't ready for that yet. 

Cisco was transferred to our rescue.  He was not forced to interact with us in any way for about 3 months.   We did not pet him, we did not pick him up, we just left him alone.  We were very patient and took things very slowly.  After a few months he would come up to us and we would give him just a little pet, a second or two, then worked his way up to longer pet sessions. 

Flooding Cisco in any way is a big trigger for his PTSD and he will warn and bite if he is forced to interact with you before he is ready.  We took our time and allowed him to come to us when he was ready which has worked wonderfully. 

After a year with us, Now he is so affectionate and loving.  He accepts pets from me, I can pick him up as well.  He still had a major issue with getting a flat collar or harness put on (total fear trigger).  Cutting his nails and cleaning his ears are extremely stressful for him and he needs to be muzzled and worked with calmly and slowly.

Cisco will give very clear signals that he has had enough and when he does, his human must respect that and leave him alone.  Of you ignore his clear signals, this could result in triggering Cisco's fear and he will go into protection mode.

When he goes into a new home, his fear will return and his new human must understand that they cannot flood him or force him to interact.  Just like we did.  This will take months.  His new human must be patient, kind, and understanding.  

You must be able to fully read the body language of a dog if you would like to adopt Cisco..

No first time dog owners.  No children.  No future children.  No large dogs.  No homes with multiple dogs.  

Cisco will be your best loving friend forever.  But he will not trust any new person 100%

Cisco should not live with children they are too unpredictable.  He has been fine with cats and all the small dogs he has met and lived with. He is very fearful of large dogs. He is very scared of many dogs at one time and will bolt and scream in fear.  Dog parks are a HUGE NO for Cisco.

He is house trained and potties outside.  We have pee pads down in case we are out too long and he will use them if necessary. 
He walks wonderfully on leash and should never be off leash and never taken to off leash dog parks.  All interactions must be in a controlled environment.  It only takes one thing to trigger his fear and he will bolt. 

Cisco is not suitable for the first time or inexperienced dog owner.  He requires a human that has the knowledge of fearful dogs and their body language. Please do not apply or inquire if you are a first time dog owner or if you've only experienced working with easy dogs. 

His adoption fee is $295. 
He has been neutered, microchipped, vaccinated, and has had his dental, deworming and flea treatment. 
A home visit and adoption application is required.

If you are interested in adopting Cisco, please go to our website and submit the online adoption application.  A home visit is also required. 

Please copy and paste the following link into your web browser.

http://lowermainlandhumanesociety.org/adoption-application/

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Ozzie and I've had a pretty rough life up until I became part of the SSRR family. The doctors think I was hit by a car and my owner waited about 6 weeks before surrendering me to the local shelter. The shelter really couldn't help me so it wasn't looking good and then the wonderful SSRR family decided to take me in and help me feel better.

I had a dislocated hip and was going to require some major surgery. However, before the surgery could happen I had to get my skin infection cleared up and that took another 3 weeks. By the time I was able to have surgery I had almost learned to live with the pain and walk with my foot turned out. BUT, thanks to many people who loved me enough to donate toward my care I was able to have the hip surgery and go home to my foster.

I'm doing great and resumed full doggie activity. The surgery made such a difference and it was so exciting when I finally got to play with my foster brothers and sisters. I have fit in well and become another member of the pack. They love me here and I love them too, but I would love to find my forever family!

My foster mom says I am SUPER sweet and I love lots of attention! I'm smart and learn quickly. I am housebroken and I know how to sit although I don't do it often (my therapist uses it to strengthen my leg so it's not fun anymore). I know to stay and I walk very well on a leash. There are no children in our house now, but I have been around them at the park and they do not bother me. I actually like all the pets and sweet things they say. I am completely food motivated, so if I need to learn something there is definitely a way to get me to do it!

If you are looking for a loving, sweet, loyal rotti to call your own I am your guy! Please ask my foster mom questions about me, she loves to talk about me!

"The harder the battle, the sweeter the victory!" My name is Baker Mayfield! I have had a few fumbles in my life but I am ready to score a touchdown! I am a handsome, 5 year old, 87lb., Pit mix. I have a lot of energy and need a privacy fenced in yard to train in! My favorite play on the field is cuddling. I am looking for a forever home without any other dogs. My adoption fee is $150 and includes my spay/neuter, vaccinations, wellness exam, heartworm test, and microchip! If you're interested in meeting/adopting me, please visit www.rescueonespringfield.com/our-adoption-process/adoption-application/ and fill out the form! We do adopt out of state with vet references and video home check. *Adopter is responsible for coming to get the dog and returning the dog if the adoption does not work out* 

Don't forget to LIKE us on Facebook!-www.facebook.com/rescueonespringfield

*Remember, dogs are pack animals. Because of this, Rescue One does not adopt to outdoor-only homes. Pets are family and are not disposable.  Please make sure that you are 100% committed to a pet before considering adding one to your home.

animal.description:
Meet Riley! This puppy mill survivor has had quite an adventure since he was rescued at eight weeks old. Riley is a sheltie and was born without a tail and had two holes where he would pass urine. When our volunteer went to pick him up at the puppy mill, he and his very under socialized siblings were hiding in the corner of a cardboard box. Since the other puppies looked normal, they were put up for sale and given to dealers to resell at pet stores or online. The puppy mill operator refused to give up any of the other puppies or Riley’s mother. She had produced 12 litters of puppies in six years. He operates legally in Pennsylvania. 

Diagnostics showed that Riley was not just born without a tail, but he was also born with only one kidney. This is a genetic issue. Thanks to the very best care from Dr. Niles and nurse Tiara at Metropolitan Veterinary Associates, Riley had total urogenital reconstruction surgery, was treated for multiple urinary tract infections, has healed so well and since he is now UTI free for a few months is finally up for adoption! 

Riley is a typical sheltie. He likes to herd dogs and people, loves to play and is very smart. He can be a bit grabby and skittish due to his puppy mill background so an adult only home with a very secure fenced yard and another playful dog is best. Riley loves other dogs more than anything. 

Riley needs a very special and patient forever home. He has so much love to give and every day he blossoms into a more wonderful puppy. 

Riley is EXACTLY why puppy mill breeding for pet store sales is a problem and why we need Victoria’s Law here in Pennsylvania. 

To apply to adopt Riley, please go to www.findingshelter.org

animal.description:
Midnight came to us from an abusive home. She is sweet and submissive with people, allowing you to take the very food from her mouth. She has been known to show fear toward adult human males. She does better with female individuals and gentle personalities.

She would be best suited as an only dog. There are very few other dogs she gets on with. Midnight is very gentle to her humans and would be good as a family dog, seeing as she enjoys being loved on. We recommend no babies or children under 13.

Midnight is a great hunter and would be great if you have any kind of rodent problem. She kills worf rats with ease.

Midnight has a pretty, brindle coat and short hair, most of her body being black. She rarely jumps up and has deep brown eyes. She's a happy girl, her round eyes and a pink tongue being the "cutest" features about her. She's the type to cuddle up to you and let you play with her ears.

animal.description: Angel IS AVAILALBE (updated 02-02-2021).To meet any of our dogs you must first complete our online adoption application on our website. She will repay you with more love than you thought imaginable! Angel's owners wanted to surrender her to their local shelter because she became infested with ticks. She didnt even have a name her owners just called her Dog. We were contacted by a concerned animal control officer and we invited Angel to join the Coastal family. Now that the ticks are history and she is safe with us, this beauty is doing very well in her foster home. Angel is a big (90 pounds), sweet girl whos quick to learn and eager to please, but she can be stubborn and will take charge if allowed so she needs a calm, assertive handler who can give her leadership and consistency. Shes become very good on a leash, has learned some basic commands (heel, halt, sit), and continues to improve her manners and obedience.Angel is almost perfect in every way, but she tends to pick her favorite person in the household and not bond with anyone else- she will also protect them from the other members of the household (including dogs), if allowed. She would do best in a low traffic home that has GSD experience and understands dogs who need a leader.The minimum adoption donation for adults is $375 and the adoption donation for puppies is $500. animal.description: Maximus IS AVAILALBE (updated 02-02-2021).To meet any of our dogs you must first complete our online adoption application on our website. For more information and the adoption application for Maximus, please visit our website belowhttp://www.coastalgsr.org/dog_profile.php?ID=20566&name=MaximusMaximus is a total love bug with the volunteers he knows and trusts, but he's another of our long-timers. He's been with us since the beginning of 2013. Yes, 2013. When you rescue a dog from the shelter, you rarely know what you're going to get. Sometimes, they just need to get out of the shelter and decompress, which will allow them to relax and adjust to their new life. Sometimes they need more.This is Maximus. Yes, he's stunning and he's a big boy. No, we don't know what his life prior to rescue entailed, but we can only imagine. Maximus doesn't trust people he doesn't know. Potential adopters? They're all people he doesn't know. If you spend time around him, not even touching him, he'll notice you. He loves treats and tossing him treats is a sure way to get him to bookmark that face of yours. Some of our volunteers spent a week just giving him treats before moving on to walking him. Once he thinks of you as a treat dispenser, he's no longer too scared, because treats are kind of worth whatever bad things he imagines could happen. I mean, treats!Then, when you get him out, you'll notice he's cautious, but he loves going on walks so much that he's willing to put up with the geeky human at his side.We don't know what happened to him, but we're pretty sure it was nothing. A whole lot of nothing. No socialization, no attention, no training, no love, and no promise of a better day. After you've taken him on a few walks, you'll notice his demeanor change. He loves walks almost as much as treats. I mean, walks!Even though he loves walking with you, he won't be a cuddly, leaning against your side kind of guy just yet. Trust comes slowly. Take it slow and, after a while, you'll notice that he's seeking affection. Once he trusts you, well, there's no end to his adorableness and affection. He loves belly rubs, giving kisses, playing catch, completing an obedience command with flair and then looking at you for praise... he's the whole package. He's going to need an adopter who can go slowly with him. Someone who is a strong handler and doesn't have a busy household. A local adopter who can come spend time getting to know him before adopting him. We wouldn't put Maximus in a home with young children, because that would be overwhelming for him. This stunner is looking for a person or a couple of people with whom he can build trust and a life.Could that be you?The minimum adoption donation for adults is $375 and the adoption donation for puppies is $500. This amount only partially covers the cost of veterinary care, boarding fees, and other miscellaneous expenses involved in the temporary care and adoption of our dogs and is tax deductible. The adoption donation provides that all dogs will be spayed or neutered, receive current vaccinations, and are microchipped. If not, arrangements will be made on an individual basis ( i.e., puppies who will need to be altered by 6 mos old). Special consideration may be given to those willing to adopt older dogs or dogs with physical problems.

animal.description: Missy IS AVAILALBE (updated 02-02-2021).To meet any of our dogs you must first complete our online adoption application on our website. For more information and the adoption application for Missy, please visit our website belowhttp://www.coastalgsr.org/dog_profile.php?ID=20090&name=MissyThere is no line of people trying to adopt Missy. Who can say why, but it's shocking!Sure, shes a senior who is around 12 years old. Missy was adopted years ago, but, sadly, her adopter passed away and she's back with us. OK, shes on prescription food for some GI issues. It's true, she's more of a one person kind of dog who would rather share all of her time with you over being the life of some big social gathering. They're gross. You can catch COVID-19 at large social gatherings. She's trying to keep you healthy. Of course, she wants to be the only dog in the home. She doesn't like cats. Oh, and she's a senior with arthritis in her hips and takes Metacam for that. Yes, she's also now on medication for seizures, because she had a small one and we sent her to a neurologist who preformed a spinal tap (to rule out meningitis), thought her pituitary gland looked normal, ruled out Cushing's disease, imaged her four ways to Friday, ruled out any tumors in her brain, put her on Zonisamide (for epilepsy), and she hasn't had a seizure since. Talk about being vetted.Adopt a seizure free gal pal!Here's what you're missing: a dog who will be your ride of die. A GSD who is potty trained, crate trained, good in the house, wants to be with you at all times, but doesn't freak out if you leave the house because separation anxiety would make her appear needy and she doesn't even like saying that word. A dog who loves going on walks and doesn't need them kept short because you're judging her age. She can walk and walk and walk and still find time to chase squirrels. You'd be missing out on the best dog her foster has ever fostered (but can't adopt, because, when things go back to 'normal,' she'll be traveling half the month). Every day you don't adopt her is a day you won't know the love of a senior dog, which is the truest love on earth. animal.description: Khaleesi IS AVAILALBE (updated 02-02-2021).To meet any of our dogs you must first complete our online adoption application on our website. For more information and the adoption application for Khaleesi, please visit our website belowhttp://www.coastalgsr.org/dog_profile.php?ID=21789&name=KhaleesiMost of us fumble and stumble our way through life forever wondering what our true purpose might be. Not Khaleesi. She knows with 100 percent certainty, just as sure as she knows that car rides are fun and grass is tasty, that she was put on this earth to be part of a family. What she doesnt know is why its taking so gosh-darn long! Now almost 7 years old, Khaleesi has been dealt some truly lousy hands by fate. She was raised in a loving home early on, but got rehomed because one of the old dogs in the house didn't get along with her. We don't know anything about that home, but Khaleesi ended up in a high kill shelter overweight and unable to walk. Her chip was still registered to her original owners who were contacted but they were not in a position to take her back and her current owners made it clear they didn't want her. Even though we didn't need another medical dog, Coastal couldnt stand by and let her be abandoned/discarded yet again. So we agreed to take her into the rescue and assume her medical care and the journey began. Unfortunately, fate wasnt quite done messing with Khaleesi, and following an initial operation where pins and plates were put into her legs, she contracted MRSA, necessitating another surgery to remove the pins and plates. Complications ensued, as did more surgeries and treatments, casts, splints, enforced crate rest, foul-tasting medicines, and on and on. Two and a half years have passed since her ordeal started, enough time to crush just about anyones spirit, but, through it all, Khaleesi has been a real trouper. Now, thanks to the excellent care of her vets and foster mom, shes largely overcome her injuries (she still wears a splint and needs to be helped while walking), and is more than ready, willing, and able to finally achieve her lifes purpose of being a cherished member of a family. This beautiful girl has so much love to give, and shes sick and tired of holding it in, doggone it!Khaleesi adores people and bonds easily. Shes extremely observant and engaged, a quick study, food/treat motivated, good in the house, not destructive, has ears softer than mink, and sheds much less than your average GSD. Shes an outstanding watchdog and an effective deterrent against pesky uninvited solicitors, but can also be trained to 'not' bark at someone like your mailman, fairly quickly. She does tend to bark at other dogs she encounters on walks, but has made friends with the ones at her foster moms house with a proper introduction. For more information and the adoption application for Apollo, please visit our website belowhttp://www.coastalgsr.org/dog_profile.php?ID=21862&name=ApolloApollo is the proud father of our H litter that was born in 2017. (The mother was Gretchen, who was also available and has been adopted.) Their owner was a back yard breeder who was not able to care for Apollo, Gretchen, nor the H litter, so Coastal GSR took them all in, because we leave no dog behind. Apollo is 8 1/2 years old and has been ready since he was rescued to experience a real life. He doesn't ask for much. Just a nice place to lay inside and outdoors. He was primarily a back yard dog with his previous owner and wasn't socialized. He likes female dogs - no male dogs please. There are a couple of volunteers that he does like and he prefers men to women. If you have GSD experience and are the kind of person who knows that some dogs need more time to come out of their shell, especially ones who were just kept in a backyard and asked to breed over and over, then you're the kind of person this handsome boy has been waiting to meet. Apollo is good with female dogs and male humans, but is timid around people he doesn't know, as he was never socialized in his previous home.The minimum adoption donation for adults is $375 and the adoption donation for puppies is $500. This amount only partially covers the cost of veterinary care, boarding fees, and other miscellaneous expenses involved in the temporary care and adoption of our dogs and is tax deductible. The adoption donation provides that all dogs will be spayed or neutered, receive current vaccinations, and are microchipped. If not, arrangements will be made on an individual basis ( i.e., puppies who will need to be altered by 6 mos old). Special consideration may be given to those willing to adopt older dogs or dogs with physical problems.

animal.description: Mimi IS AVAILALBE (updated 02-02-2021).To meet any of our dogs you must first complete our online adoption application on our website. For more information and the adoption application for Mimi, please visit our website belowhttp://www.coastalgsr.org/dog_profile.php?ID=22104&name=MimiDo you know what it's like to lose your human in a car accident, land at the shelter, get rescued, have major back surgery, then wait for someone to fall in love with you and take you home? Mimi does.You won't meet a sweeter nor peppier GSD than Mimi. She's been through a lot, but she's remained in great spirits and is always willing to cover you in kisses.Mimi's human was killed in a car accident and she was taken to a shelter by the extended family. We rescued her and noticed she was wobbly in the rear, so she went to see our vet. She had an exam, blood work, and x-rays, but our vet said she needed to see a specialist, so we scheduled an appointment with a really well known neurologist. He wanted to do a genetic test for DM before doing an MRI, but she didn't have the genes, so we kept moving forward.Mimi had an MRI that showed spinal surgery was an option which could better her life, so she went to Dr. Berry at Southern California Veterinary Specialty Hospital for a hemilaminectomy. Her surgery was a great success! So much so that instead of using a sling to help her walk because her back legs were weak, we used a sling to help keep her under 30mph, as she had use of her back legs and wanted to gogogogogo! She's been doing therapy to strengthen her back legs, is doing great, has a great attitude, and enjoys hanging out in the yard with her toys. We know what an amazing soul she is and we know someone else out there will see what we see: a ridiculously sweet, gentle, energetic, fun, lovable girl who isn't going to let a medical issue slow her down one bit. This classic beauty is great with people and gets along with other dogs, knows 'sit' and 'down,' and can't wait to have a family again. She can get protective of what she thinks is hers, so she'd do best with a GSD savvy family.The minimum adoption donation for adults is $375 and the adoption donation for puppies is $500. animal.description: Welcome Canelo to the Marley's Mutts family! Canelo came into our foster care after he was advocated by the shelter staff at Pima county because he was surrendered to the shelter because he became paralysed due to a herniated disc issue. His former family was unable to care for him and deal with his new needs. Canelo was severely overweight and had some very bad urine burns on his sensitive belly. His foster mom has to get his weight down and treat his burns before he could be outfitted with a wheelchair. This lucky pup has come a long way! He has slimmed down, gained some much needed muscle in his front legs, and cleared up his belly burns! Joeys Paw stepped in and donated a brand new wheelchair for him so he could be mobile again and give him a new lease on life! He has taken to his new wheels like a champ and is now looking for a home! Canelo can't be picky about new people and will get snarky, but he's just scared of new people and things. It just takes him a min to recognise that new people aren't out to hurt him. Were pretty sure that he never met new people at his previous home. Canelo does need a lot of daily care and cleaning up after. He no longer has control over his bladder and bowels and uses doggy diapers. He's basically a human toddler who can't walk just yet. If you would like to meet this wonderful wheelie dog, apply to adopt him today! If you are interested in adopting a Marley's Mutts please fill out an application at http://marleysmutts.org/adoptionprocess/

animal.description:
Hi, there. I'm Lenny, a big fella finding his way in this brave new world.

I'm a shy guy who is becoming more social and trusting. My crate is my safe space, but I like going for walks and romping around with playful dogs. Cats are OK, but new people, kids and loud noises can be scary! Give me a little time to get to know and trust you. We'll be friends in no time, I promise. My dream home would be one with patient adults who can help my build my confidence and don't mind my quirks, and a dog friend (or three!) to play and snuggle with.

I'm an older fella with some manageable medical issues. I have arthritis and allergies, and I need daily meds and supplements to help me feel my best. My meds are about $88 a month. 

Things can be pretty frightening for me sometimes, but I'll feel a lot braver with you at my side. Are you the human hero I'm looking for? Apply to meet me today!

animal.description:
Located in Battle Creek, Michigan. Fully vetted. 6yrs old. 

Are you comfortable just hanging out at home? Maybe going out into your fenced backyard, gardening or relaxing with a book and cold drink under a tree? Do you run short errands around town occasionally?

Guess what? Dilly does too!

He's not interested in hanging with any other animals! Just you! Oh, and your friends. (as long as they don't bring their pets!) kids might be cool too, as long as they are cool with him!

Dilly is a gentle giant! He loves kids, and all humans--and is not shy. He is around 70lbs currently. He would benefit from a fenced yard because he needs safe confinement to avoid chasing squirrels or other animals. A fenced yard is mandatory however rural households may be considered under certain conditions. Dilly walks great on a leash, and is perfect in the house and very relaxed. He is around 5 years old and fully vetted--neutered and vaccinated. 

He enjoys relaxed activities outside and tends to be a lounger in the house. He will play with toys and utilize chews. Has no issues being left loose and alone in the house. Has been reactive/super anxious to crates and doesn't need one, nor do we recommend one for him. 

Please private message us at www.facebook.com/allspecieskinship to meet him! If you do NOT have Facebook, call 877-596-7776. Dilly's adoption fee has been sponsored by his former adopter who could no longer keep him.

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Dilly does not enjoy the company of other companions. He is however VERY people-friendly!

BIO:
Elsa estimated to be 13yrs old was found as a stray in the Tampa Bay area and had clearly suffered from neglect for a long period of time. She was completely forlorn and had no spirit left. She was also suffering from an inability to produce tears and her eyes were so crusted over she had become accustomed to sleeping with her eyes open because she couldnt shut her eyelids. (this photo in comments) These days Elsa is a happy dog! She runs around the house and yard, wags her tail and her NEW favorite thing is getting KISSES on the cheek from her foster mom!

Would you be interested in sending a surprise to help Elsa's foster parent care for her? If the dog is over 13 or has medical needs we will be including a care list from the foster parent's via amazon.
https://www.amazon.com/hz/wishlist/ls/1FJCO9MI0A4SI?ref_=wl_share

You can help sponsor her medical care by visiting http://www.igrescue.com/html/donate/financial_contributions.shtml
Make sure to list that you would like your donation to assist Elsa-Gulf Coast Rescue

*Please note that Elsa is unable to be adopted, until the Gulf Coast Rep and Rescue Vet give clearance. If by chance you would be interested in her please feel free to email us at igrescuegulfcoast@gmail.com and when she is ready if your application is approved you can be notified.

animal.description:
Status: Hospice
Location: Florida
BIO:
Cassie at 13 yrs was found as a stray in the panhandle of FL. After quite a bit of testing and health setbacks she was diagnosed with small intestine overgrowth and put on a daily supplement that has really helped. Cassie is a very funny girl who gets old lady zoomies frequently. She also likes to play the 'high ten game' with her foster mom. This consists of Cassie doing a bow and the foster mom bows back and then taps Cassie's Shoulders then in turn Cassie jumps up and 'High Tens' the foster mom on the knees. Cassie is a cuddle bug and has a cheeky attitude and ready to find her forever family =) 

Update: 4/9/20- Cassie has recently gone fully blind and with her age we have discussed with her foster mom about marking her as a hospice foster. Cassie is an amazing girl; but with her age, being blind, as well as having a hard time handling change we believe this is the best option for her at this time. Her foster mom has also let us know that she is currently on a homemade diet for both her meals morning and night.

Would you be interested in sending a surprise to help Cassie's foster parent's care for her? If the dog is over 13 or a hospice foster we will be including a care list from the foster parent's via amazon. 
https://www.amazon.com/hz/wishlist/ls/1G8OLH5IXF26F?ref_=wl_share

You can help sponsor their medical care by visiting http://www.igrescue.com/html/donate/financial_contributions.shtml
Make sure to list that you would like your donation to assist Cassie-Gulf Coast Rescue 

*Please note that if a foster is classified as Hospice we are happy to let them live out the remainder of their time with rescue.
