animal.description:
Meet this handsome fella named Rebel! He originally came into the shelter December 5, 2019 as a stray and was never reclaimed. He was adopted and now back as of November 2020 when his owners were moving. He is now awaiting his chance at a great life. Rebel came in with a bad ear and skin infection and after a trip to the vet for a full exam he’s got a good check up and should be on the mend. (Will need a home that can clean his ears at least 1 time per week and probably good for him to be on a once a day allergy medication.) He was taken care of food wise he’s a healthy 75 pounds. Despite the discomfort he felt he is the sweetest gentle natured boy who is full of happiness and love to share. Rebel is around 6 years old and is current on his vaccinations,& now neutered. He keeps his kennel neat inside and loves to snuggle up in blankets on his bed. Will thrive once in a loving home where he feels safe and loved. Walks great on the leash and will bring a lifetime of unconditional love and companionship to the lucky person or family that adopts him. Seems to get along fine with most other dogs too. Stop by the shelter for a visit with Rebel today!! 
If you have another dog and are interested in meeting another potential new furry member please bring him or her to the shelter and meet on neutral ground before adopting. No need to shuffle the animals around any more than necessary. Please know that 1 mosquito bite can create heart worms and they can be fatal if not treated. It is VERY important to keep your pets healthy and protected by keeping them on a once a month heart worm and flea/tick prevention. These animals are counting on you as their owner to provide them with lots a love and the proper health care so PLEASE make sure you are aware and prepared before adopting. Owning a pet is an extra expense and responsibility but is so worth every minute and penny you invest in them. They will add lots of joy and unconditional love if given a fair chance.
The shelter is open Mon.-Fri. 10-1, 2-5 and Sat. 10-4. Adopt a homeless pet and save a life. If you can not adopt right now come out and volunteer and make a difference in the lives of these animals while they await their FOREVER home.

animal.description: Ginger (DOB 2007) came to FCSR as an owner-surrender, sort of... the owner asked her son to take Ginger to the Animal Shelter. A friend of the son stepped in and said let me find a rescue so the friend called FCSR.  Ginger has been in a medical foster home since coming to us on 11/9/19.  Before coming to us, she was living on a porch by herself, the owner fed her once a day and she had to go to the bathroom on the porch.  Poor Ginger was eaten up with fleas and her skin was in horrible condition with unbelievable hair loss. Ginger tested HW negative and has a clean bill of health with the exception of allergies.  At one point in her life, Ginger had an ear ablation on her right ear, however, her left ear in good condition. Here is the report from her foster family: “Ginger is a very sweet girl. Considering Ginger has not had a lot of attention in the past, she has trust issues.  She does not like to go out into the fenced yard; she likes to be walked on a leash.  In the beginning, she was scared of walking on the grass. Ginger will come sit on your lap once she trusts you, which took us about a month.  She doesn't give lots of kisses yet and is still trying to adjust to a new life in a house with a bed.  Her personality is starting to come out. She loves to root & rub on the blankets.  Ginger's favorite spot in on the end of the sofa; she needs a place to feel safe.  She sleeps on her own bed in our bedroom.  Ginger is a work in progress and her hair is starting to grow back.  She originally did not have a name, but her coat looks like it is going to be a beautiful light red, so we call her Ginger We got her a couple t-shirts and a sweatshirt to stay warm when it's cooler.  She gets along fine with her foster dog sisters; she hasn't had any interactions with cats.  If you are interested in Ginger, please fill out an adoption application at floridacocker.org. For more information, please call 813-245-1833 or contact info@floridacocker.org

animal.description:
Last weigh-in: 63.2 lbs

Foster Update 02/2020: 
Reva is still getting comfortable with people and is very gentle. She is starting to get used to us and even allows an occasional belly rub. She has a lot of potential and just needs someone with patience to help her feel confident. 

Reva is described as: Slightly active, Leash trained & Gentle. 

Meet Reva!
We were alerted to a pup named Reva that is living under a house and needed immediate rescue. According to neighbors, she was born under the house and has lived there with her mom, Lady, for the last 11 years! She was never allowed inside the house. The owner told neighbors he had her spayed as a puppy and she has not had human touch after that day.
Over a month prior to our involvement the owner of the house sold it and moved out - taking only Lady with him. Reva chased after the car but was too scared to get in. For the following six weeks, Reva continued her daily routine of roaming the neighborhood during the day and retreating to her abandoned house at night, crying out for her missing family. Luckily, her neighbors have been providing her food and water but they knew she needed medical care and were trying to come up with a plan. While searching for help on Facebook, one of the neighbors came across a dog that looked just like Lady on a local Lost & Found Pet page!
After a quick message to the finder, it was discovered that the dog was Lady (now named Zooey) and had been found wandering on Sam Cooper near 240 a few weeks prior. The ladies swapped contact info and reached out to Streetdog Foundation with this incredible story.
It was discovered that Lady (aka Zooey) had escaped her new yard. We think she might have been trying to find her way back to Reva. Zooey is now adopted by her finder and both she and the neighbor are helped us!
September 21st we set out to set a humane trap and get her safe. Within no time at all she walked right in the crate where some Pirtles chicken was waiting for her. This girls long ordeal is over! Next we move on to healing her both mentally and physically.
For the physical part Doc noted she has juvenile cataracts that will develop over time but otherwise, with the exception of a couple of tooth extractions, is in very good health. Mentally we will now give her the space and time to acclimate to her new life.

animal.description:
Last Weigh-in: 71.8 lbs

Foster Update 11/2020: Stormy prefers to be the only pup. 

Foster Update 7/2020: While Stormy is kid-friendly, she would thrive best in a home with older children (11 years + up). 

Foster Update 2/21/2019: Stormy's foster says she is highly trainable and very smart. She does well in a car, likes to fetch, and loves her toys. He also describes her as obedient, playful, affectionate, and goofy. 

Foster Update 11/26/2019: Stormy is super sweet, but when she gets excited, she gets a little mouthy. We are working on it, but it is a work in progress. She has not had an accident in the house and is really well crate trained. It's hard to gauge her true energy level because she is heartworm positive. She is super smart and has learned her name, sit, come, down, and bed in a matter of three weeks. She will be a great family dog, not to mention she is a wonderful guard dog. She has a deep ferocious bark, but little do they know, she would kill them with kisses.

Stormy is house trained and crate trained. She is moderately active and it is unknown how she would do with cats. 

--------------------------------------------

October 7, 2019 in Memphis was rough. We had experienced incredibly hot temperatures for the prior month and no rain. Literally NO RAIN for 3 + weeks. On this night it rained almost 5 inches. It was the kind of storm that sneaks up on you - the sky opens up with rain and next thing you know the streets are flooded. The sky lit up all night long with lightning. And thunder. Rolls of thunder from far away and then blasts that woke up the whole house. This went on for several hours throughout the night and into the early morning hours.

That being the case, we were absolutely devastated when our volunteer that reads the intake emails (yes, everyone at Streetdog Foundation is a volunteer) opened up the first email and saw this picture. This sweet pup, who had recently given birth, was abandoned in a wire crate that night. Our hearts were shattered when we realized that she was left outside with no cover. No protection from the torrential downpour. No one to comfort or love her while the storms rumbled on all night. She was dumped with nothing but this crate and the tattered collar around her neck.
We were full. Every foster in our program had a foster pup (or two or three) in their home. We even had several dogs in boarding. But we had to say yes to this amazing girl. We had to have a chance to prove to her that not all humans are bad and that she is worthy of love.

She received a full checkup by ‘Doc’ at Grace Animal Hospital. This sweet girl tested positive for heartworms and had never been spayed. Well, we are on top of it and getting her healthy! As soon as those nasty heartworms are gone this girl will be ready to settle into her forever home! Forever Safe. Forever Loved. Forever Dry.

* Behaviors not listed have yet to be tested.

animal.description:
Stone was found standing in the middle of a road by a kind man. He immediately contacted us because Stone had numerous scabs, open wounds, hair loss and scars all over the head, legs and body.  Both of his front legs were swollen. His tail and one of his legs had been broken. He was in horrible condition! We got him to the vet as soon as possible and discovered one of his front legs was possibly fractured recently. He was also loaded with parasites. Due to the location and shape of some of his scars, our vet told us he was probably a "bait dog", meaning dog fighters used him as bait to train the fighting dogs. Despite his condition and his past, Stone is so sweet to everyone!! He loves playing with dogs through the gate of his run and in the outside run.  He still acts like a puppy sometimes! He is food protective so he would have to be fed separately if with another dog. Our staff and volunteers have been giving him so much love and attention, and he is definitely enjoying his new life.  Stone's date of birth is 12/6/2017 and he weighs about 50 pounds. 

Stone spent some time in a foster home and his foster mom told us this about him, "Stone is so gentle and kind. He walks well on a leash, takes treats really gently, and is just a calm, quiet boy."

You can submit an adoption application for this sweet boy at http://www.fayettefcar.com/applicationform, where you can also review FCAR’s adoption requirements.

All FCAR adoptable dogs have been spayed or neutered, are current on all vaccines, on flea/tick and heartworm prevention, microchipped, and come with a 30-day pet health guarantee. The adoption fee is $95 with an approved application. A fenced yard is required for Stone.

animal.description:
***COURTESY POST***


Meet Gracie...an approximately 2 year old spayed female pit bull mix.  Gracie is the definition of a survivor. This poor girl likely never knew the kindness of humans until her rescue in November of 2019.  She and her puppy were living on the streets and spent their days trying to find enough food just to survive.  Humans weren't kind to her and she became very fearful. When it finally became time to be rescued of wasn't an easy task.  Gracie was terrified and while she wanted to trust she couldn't get passed her fear.  Finally, a humane trap was brought in to bring her to safety.  That was the beginning of the beautiful relationship with her foster Mom Michelle.  Michelle was there from day one and has committed herself to helping Gracie come out of her shell and find the forever home she deserves.  Gracie did test positive for heartworms and has taken a round of doxycycline and is currently on heartworm prevention.  Her skin issues are caused by Demodex.  It's a non contagious skin condition and she is currently being treated. As you can see from her before and after pictures she's come so far.  Gracie loves kids and she gets along well with other dogs.  She is also housebroken.  Gracie has also been spayed, microchipped and is current on vaccinations.  

A fenced yard and home visit are REQUIRED to adopt Gracie. For more information please contact her foster Mom Michelle 225-223-0910

This is Violet. This goofy goblin wants to remind everyone that she’s still looking for a home! She’s only 3 and ready to be your BFF for the next 10+ years! She’s hilarious! She loves to play! She loves car rides! Walks! Hikes (as long as it’s not raining!) Zoomies! Her person/people! Blankets! Dog beds! Big fan of West Paw brand toys! (It’s her preference, I don’t ask questions.) House trained! Loves her crate! Walks well on leash and is not leash reactive! Listens to commands! Comes when called! She doesn’t love most other dogs but *could* live with the right one (probably a mellow, adult, male.) She doesn’t want to live with kids, not yours or anyone else’s. Not a big fan of strangers, meaning she probably won’t like your sister/grandma/husbands 3rd cousin/obnoxious drunk uncle, etc. Would prefer to skip out on thanksgiving dinner festivities and just come out for some pie after everyone has left (same.) Doesn’t want to go to your fiancées parents house for a cookout. Really doesn’t care about your friends dog park coffee and gossip meet ups. Now, if you need a dog to go on a coffee/beer pick up run with you, she’s down and ready to ignore everyone, just don’t expect her to make friends with Nancy or her chihuahua in the line next to you. She’s a live and let live (in our respective corners) kinda gal.

PLEASE DO NOT INQUIRE ABOUT VIOLET IF:
-ANYONE under 18 lives in your home
-You have multiple other dogs
-You have cats
-You have roommates
-You are against crates
-You are not open to balanced training


*PLEASE NOTE: All dogs are in foster care all over MA & RI. They are NOT at the cat shelter in Acushnet, which is the address listed on Petfinder. There are ONLY cats there. We do not set up meet and greets with dogs until after you've been approved to adopt. Please do not email asking us if you can come by and meet a dog the same day.*

animal.description:
Krim is a strong, loving, cautious, alert, silly, playful and full of character girl. She was adopted out as a pup and returned when other members of the family brought home dogs that she couldn't get along with, thus causing her to lose her home. We believe Krim needs a home that loves the American bully cross with a Staffordshire or Pitbull. This breed combination is extremely loyal, affectionate and protective, so experience is absolutely needed for an adopter. Experience with either breed or both is a plus!

Krim learns quickly, walks well on a leash, takes to training like a fish to water, swims in water like a true fish, plays with toys and doesn't mind sharing with her person, and will truly be a partner til the end. She has shown an inclination to attach to her handlers, so multiple person households have to work with her equally. We advise no little children as she is a big girl and needs an adult leader as well as a home that can focus on her needs. We also are looking for an active household that enjoys being outside, walking/hiking and exploring, this young lady needs her mind to be nourished by mother nature's medicinal presence.

Krim is currently in a training program where she learns basic obedience, leash skills and socializing alongside new people and dogs. We expect an owner to be open to training and commit to learning about Krim alongside us.

If you are interested in adopting Krim, please fill out an application at https://www.dogsaredeservingrescue.com/adoptable-dogs/adoption-application/

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website. All of our dogs and cats are in foster homes and we have no paid staff. If you have questions concerning a specific animal, PLEASE fill out an application and the foster parent will be in touch. We will not arrange any home visits with any of our dogs and cats until your application is processed. Please understand our foster parents are precious to our 2nd Chance family; without them we cannot function, so we do our best to not burden them with multiple appointments. Our foster parents will choose their top 3 applications and arrange home visits with these applicants. The adopter will be chosen at that time. The process can take anywhere from a week to a month. We want to make sure our little furry ones are placed in their 'forever home' and never have to go through a rehoming again!Well hello my name is Poodah. I am an elderly gentleman but I still have some spunk left in me. I'm not fond of being picked up and my legs are deformed but that is probably from birth. ( I of course know but have no way of telling the humans around me :)I hang out with the other ranch dude and today I even played with this young pup named Sally who kept jumping on me and knocking me over but I have to admit it was fun and I kept going back for more :)PS my foster mommy says I need to tell you I REALLY don't like baths and getting my legs played with doesn't make me happy.Please fill out an adoption application:
Adoption application (Dog)
Adoption Application (Cat)

Please understand we do not adopt out dogs to
families with children under the age of 5. We do not adopt dogs to renters. Some dogs will have fence requirements while others may not.

A pet is a lifetime commitment. The dogs and cats in our system find themselves there, for the most part, because their humans did not have the same loyalty to them as they did to their owners. We do not take the adoption process lightly, and will do everything in our power to make sure the animal is placed correctly the first time around for your sake and theirs. Thank you for choosing to adopt not shop!

animal.description:
Celeste and Junior have quite the story to tell and are such special pups! 

These two adorable and bonded besties were found starving and emaciated living under a house in rural Texas (see pics). They were left to fend for themselves for years that way and clung to one another for support.  Junior is so good with Celeste, he even lets her take food right out of his mouth!! 

When they were finally rescued, these poor babies were in rough shape but with time, love and some healthcare they are now thriving. Despite all they lived through, Junior and Celeste are the most sweet and loving dogs and will steal your heart. You need to meet them to understand just how sweet and awesome they are! They love to snuggle with their human and each other. Their foster mom is completely smitten!!! 

Junior and Celeste live on a farm with their foster mom and do well with other dogs and even Alpacas! Junior can tend to be a little too interested in cats, so we think a cat free home is ideal. Celeste had a double perianal hernia which has now been fixed but she still wears diapers in the event she has a little bit of a leak. Her favorite pair of “undies” are her hot pink and leopard and she is always up to date on the latest fashions :-) We know these two are not the easiest to find a home for, but we are confident their special someone is out there.  

All of our puppies and dogs come up to date on vaccinations, microchipped, spayed/neutered and dewormed. To fill out an application to meet this super special  pair, please visit www.snarrnortheast.org 

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING

**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder, so there are sometimes discrepancies between what is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $375 for adults / Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

animal.description: Striker is looking for his forever home! This beautiful 3 year-old boxer mix loves to play fetch and run around a yard, but also loves taking a nap. He is a studious boy and completed a professional board & train program in Saratoga, so he knows all of his obedience commands. Striker isn’t for everyone, but he could be for you! If you have experience with anxious dogs and are looking for a new hiking partner and best friend, Striker is your man. He can be dog selective, but currently lives with two others. He is on medication for his anxiety and doing well; this medication will need to continue, but is very inexpensive. Because of his anxiety, he is too nervous to be around small children and really needs a confident owner with dog handling experience to give him the best life. If you fit the bill, Striker will be your best pal!  Striker is in foster near Albany NY.  If interested, please submit an application on our site, www.mountainrottierescue.net!

She needs someone who will give her time and not push the petting issues. She is terrified after being abused. I can now pick her up and pet as long as slow approach. She needs a fenced area since she does not tolerate a leash. 

She needs to be an only dog. She is a bully and starts a ruckus with the other small dogs. She will go outside to potty as long as weather not terrible. She will also use a puppy pad. 

Sophie was rescued from local shelter. She had been surrendered then adopted out to a house with 5 kids. She did not do well and was returned 2 days later. 

She is sweet, but terrified of being picked up and petted. . Working on her fears.

update: No steps for Gizmo. He has crippled front feet. Weighs 20+ pounds. Must have fenced yard, he does not walk on a leash. He must be sedated for grooming and vetting every 3-4 months. He will not allow you to groom him, listen to his heart, check his ears, etc. He is crate trained and will go outside to potty if you escort him out. Gizmo came into rescue when his owner passed away. He had never been groomed. He does not want to be touched for grooming or vetting and does not want to be picked up. Was sedated for grooming and vetting. 

He is sweet and confused as to what has happened. He is doing well with crate training and will go out if asked. He will potty in house if you don't watch him.

animal.description:
MEET SWEET PEA: Are you looking for a new pea to add to your pod?! Sweet Pea joined our rescue in November 2019.  She lives for belly rubs and dinner time!

Sweet Pea’s personality is true to her name, she is truly a sweetheart who loves being near her people. Sweet Pea is a 13 year old shih tzu mix and is roughly 30 pounds.

Sweet Pea is special needs as she is diabetic and blind. She is not fond of her insulin shots (for diabetes) and needs someone who is patient and willing to work with her as long it takes for her to get used to it. Long term medical care is required for Sweet Pea, regular follow ups with a veterinarian to make sure she’s on the right dosage of insulin.

We are working on getting her comfortable in her new surroundings. She will do best in a home where someone is home for most of the day, as she can get nervous and cry when left alone for long periods of time. We believe this is partially due to her being newly blind. She does well in her foster home with small dogs her size and cats who do not try to interact with her. Sweet Pea does not wish to play or cuddle with other pets in the home but does not mind that they are there as long as they respect her space ‘bubble’.  Sweet Pea does best being separated from other dogs whenever food is involved.

Characteristics:  Sweet, Playful, Belly Rubs, Special Needs, Loving, Cute 
Background:  Sweet Pea was surrendered to our rescue in January 2020.
Falling in love?! EMAIL US for an adoption application for Sweet Pea!

animal.description:
Due to COVID 19, and the Illinois Shelter in Place order, we have experienced an overwhelming increase in the interest of animal adopting.  We have been inundated with more applications than we can process, as we are an all-volunteer agency.  

We do sincerely thank you for your interest in adoption.  At this time, we will only be reaching out to applicants who may be a potential match for one of our available animals.  

NOTE: WE ARE FOSTER BASED, AND ONLY FULLY APPROVED APPLICATIONS ARE SCHEDULED FOR A MEET AND GREET. 

Again, we are all volunteers, and do our best to acknowledge/respond to all applications and inquiries, in a timely manner. 

Please read the bio below - in it's entirety - before submitting an application.  

Thank you!

Soldier was a Lake County stray that was unclaimed after sitting out his old time.  He arrived in poor condition, very underweight and understandably scared.  He is about 9-10 yrs old. We have no idea how long he had been on the run fending for himself.  When he arrived to his foster home he was very unsure.  He had just been neutered and was still a tad drowsy. Foster mom set up a large crate for him in the living room. Nice cushy pillow, soft blankets, stuffed toy. He observed the comings and goings of her household for several hours. 

48 hours later: he's much more relaxed, met the remaining pack of dogs. He eats with the others.  As a typical chihuahua he may seem to be unapproachable, but it's only an act. The right people, gentle, caring, patient he will easily adapt to. 

He gets along with other dogs once he gets to know them. He doesn't play, but will cuddle with you. He is crate trained, but obviously prefers to be out.  He is potty trained.  He prefers women over men, but again, with gentleness and patience he will learn to trust. He has been around a child who is 4yrs old. She is an animal lover and knows how to respect animals.  He is also warm and loving and even grateful at times.  Applications at www.placingpawsrescue.org.

ADOPTION FEE: $350.00 The adoption fee includes all age appropriate vaccinations including rabies, HW test if age appropriate, de-worming, microchip, fecal, spay or neuter, Heartworm and flea and tick preventative.  ADOPTION PROCESS: PLEASE READ CAREFULLY The first step in the adoption process is to fill out an application online at www.placingpawsrescue.org. Once we review the applications, those applicants that are thought to be a good match will be contacted as quickly as possible. We ask that you please be patient with us as we are all volunteers. Then a telephone interview will take place, references checked and a home visit will be conducted. We will then arrange for you to meet the dog. We require that all family members, including current dogs meet the dog prior to adoption.  We put all of the known information in the animals description. If the animal is listed on the website, we are still accepting applications for that animal. We only remove the animal when the final adoption paperwork is signed. The best way to contact us is by email at placingpaws@yahoo.com. It is very difficult for the limited numbers of volunteers to return all calls. Thank you.

COVID-19 Protocol: Adoptions will be done by appointment only. If you see a pet you are interested in please call the Franklin Township Animal Shelter at: (732)-873-2500 ext. 6255 and leave a message with your name, phone number, and the name of the pet you are interested in.

You must leave a message so that we can return your call to schedule an appointment.

Sweet, affectionate, and playful --that's Syrus! He is almost 10 years of age, but don't tell him that! Syrus is full of puppy like energy, and would love to go to an active home with lots of backyard space. He was surrendered to the Franklin Township Animal Shelter post-neuter when he developed separation anxiety and related destructive behaviors after the surgery. Syrus would do best in a home where he is not left alone for any extended period of time. He loves attention and being around people, and is a pro at playing fetch! Every inquisitor, Syrus could use some additional training on leash manners, but is he attentive and simply needs direction. He cannot go to a home with cats or dogs. He may do well in a home with older children. 

Our adoption fee is $60 per pet with a discount available for adopting two animals together. All animals from the Franklin Township Animal Shelter are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and up-to-date on all age-appropriate shots prior to adoption. Dogs have also been tested for heartworm.

animal.description:
Kirk Here!

I bet you have seen me around here before because I was wescued a year ago.  Are you in interested in adopting me? Please make sure you read my entire dating profile below before inquiring or applying for me.  These humans want what is best for me so they are not going to compromise on finding me my perfect furever home.  

My foster mom says I am a very typical Westie with lots of energy. She says it is what you might call nervous energy so I need a calm but active all-adult home where I can get plenty of exercise. I am always up for an adventure and LOVE leash-walks around the neighborhood, hikes in the country on my leash, and hunting bugs in the fenced backyard.  When I am stressed or if there is too much going on around me, I displays signs of "canine compulsive disorder" including licking the air, chomping my jaws without eating, rapid blinking, and staring intently for bugs that no one else can see. I am being treated with supplements and medications and it is essential that I continue getting them going forward. 

I need people who will take the time to get to know me and my specific needs until I trust you.

My furever family:

•will be patient and understanding. Sometimes I need someone to sit with me until I am ready for my leash for a walk, someone to continually try new methods to get me to eat my supplements and medications, and someone who understands that schedule changes, sudden movements, and loud noises are terrifying for me.
•will be an all-adult household with no contact with children (living in the house or visiting).
•will have a securely fenced backyard with a locked gate.
•will not have another dog, cat or any other small creature to stalk and catch.
•will be a Westie (or similar) experienced household.
•will have experience with “difficult” personalities and will follow the guidance of the rescue.
•will have a vet team that will work with specific needs.
•will not put me in situations with humans I does not trust such as dog parks or public patios.
•will live within 1 hour of Houston, TX to minimize stress during travel and transition (Exception may be made for households within Texas demonstrating competence and expertise in handling behavioral issues).

* Please note: Kirk is safe with us and will stay that way until the right forever home is found. We absolutely will not consider a home in which he will come in contact with children nor one without the required experience.

Kirk is about 5 years old and has been fully vaccinated, neutered, and microchipped. His adoption donation is $350 which includes 6 months heartworm preventative meds, free microchip registration, and a safety harness.

If you are interested in adopting Kirk, please review the adoption process and fill out the application on our website: www.wsrh.com. *** Please describe your experience with dogs with behavioral issues.

All dogs are available until “Adoption Pending” is noted next to their names. WSRH DOES NOT HAVE A PUBLIC SHELTER. ALL OF OUR DOGS ARE FOSTERED IN PRIVATE HOMES. Approved adopters only will be invited to meet the dogs.

animal.description:
How can you resist this gentle couch potato cream puff?  Chayton’s size is closer to a Boxer and his personality is closer to an English Bulldog.  Mild mannered, laid back, and affectionate. He is quiet, but will alert when needed.  He will also bark to let you know he needs to go potty.  His speed is that of a slow trotter instead of a runner. Chayton loves food and rubber Kong toys! Given his size, he is extremely easy to handle. Chayton is good with kids and other dogs.  

Funny thing he does:  When he is playing with his canine foster brothers and sisters, he can be seen slowly jogging behind them when they play chase. (They could probably lap him twice…). It is adorable to watch as he wants to engage, but just can’t keep up with dogs that can run really fast.

Most endearing qualities: Very affectionate and loving. Loves getting attention and belly rubs. 

Skills: House broken, Crate trained, Leash trained, Kennel, Sit, Down, Heel, Rollover.

7 Years Old-72 pounds-Adoption cost $100

animal.description: Gunner likes to play with his squeaky toys, play tug with his foster mom and chase small balls around. He loves belly rubs and meeting new people. Walks are the highlight of his day unless he gets to go on a car ride and that takes top prize. He's been known to sit in the garage for hours in the dark hoping for a car ride. Gunner is brave in a thunder storm but gets nervous when the broom falls down. He likes rolling on his back in the grass and taking naps in the sun. Gunner also walks very slowly around his foster mom's plants. It's officially called trancing though I like to say he's Hunting Wabbits. Gunner is house trained, knows sit and is trustworthy being left in the house alone. He will not chew on your things or accidentally knock things over being rough. He plays well by himself tossing his toys up and chasing them around the yard. When he's excited about a toy, he'll spin circles around it. Gunner sleeps on his back with his legs sprawled in the air without a care in the world Want to learn more about Gunner? Email his foster family at low_maintenance_girl@yahoo.com. Copy and paste this link to see Gunner's shared folder on Google Drive with lots of pictures and videos of him https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1R09AcGVFach7YHVUMYCqABGUyaDM5J2F?usp=sharing

animal.description:
UPDATE NOVEMBER 17:  One of our very active volunteers took Decker home for some TLC and a break from kennel life.  He has known Decker a long time, and wrote the following:  

"Decker was awesome on his "break" from the kennel.  He's much better on a leash than he used to be when he was at the previous kennel.  I've had him at our house and he's been great with our dogs, played well with toys, and most surprisingly he hasn't seemed to care about our cats. He came nose to nose with one of our cats that was up on a table and he just smelled the cat and walking away. After that both cats stayed up on that table for a while and he didn't stalk the table or really seem to be interested in them at all. I was so happy about the change in him!"

PHOTOS:  Virtually all of our dogs have online PHOTO ALBUMS through SmugMug with LOTS of additional pictures.  Just copy and paste the link below into your browser (or simply type it in) and then search for the dog's "gallery" by name

          http://adoptasleddog.smugmug.com

VIDEOS:  In addition to photo albums, almost every dog has a video which will give you a much better "feel" for his or her personality.  NOTE:  In the new Petfinder format, it has become quite a bit more difficult to find and to play videos.  Please PAGE THROUGH the photos, looking for a photo overlaid in the center with a "play" arrow inside a circle.  This icon is white, so it can be difficult to see. 
 In many (most) cases, the video is the last photo displayed as you page through.  Just click on that photo and it will play.  Please make sure you CHECK ON THE PETFINDER VIDEO ICON, above, to see a video of this wonderful dog!  Our videos will include, at a minimum, whatever info we had on the dog upon (or shortly after) his/her arrival into our program.  There will sometimes be video updates as well.  And in every case, our Adoptions Coordinator can be emailed at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM to answer questions and provide the most current information we have on the dog.  

NOTES:  Please see video or contact our Adoptions Coordinator at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM.

ADOPTION DONATION:  $250  Before adoption, all Northern Lights dogs (regardless of whether Petfinder's symbols appear) are spayed or neutered, microchipped, heartworm negative, fully vaccinated and tested/treated for known parasites.
 
WHAT TO DO IF YOU WANT TO ADOPT THIS DOG:  Email us at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM to request an application and get started.  WE DO NOT HAVE AN ONLINE APPLICATION - you will have to request one via email.  We will review your application to determine if there is a good fit between you and/or your family and this dog.  We may suggest another dog or dog(s) if we can offer a better fit in terms of lifestyle, experience, other pets, etc.  A vet check, reference checks, and a home visit will be conducted before an adoption can be considered for approval.  
 
NORTHERN LIGHTS DOES NOT HAVE A PHYSICAL SHELTER.  We are a nonprofit rescue organization comprised of individuals who open their private homes to foster dogs in need of a second chance..  When fosters are not available, we often pay to board a dog until space is available.  New fosters and donations to pay for boarding are always desperately needed us.  Email us at KATYLIED2@AOL.COM if you are interested in donating or for information on fostering.
 
FAQ:  For information regarding our organization, as well as adoption policies and practices, please visit our Petfinder Home Page at WWW.NORTHERNLIGHTS.PETFINDER.COM.
 
 
NOTICE:  In the vast majority of cases, the dogs in our program and rescued from shelters, and Northern Lights has no means by which to collect or verify a dog's history.  We work in concert with our veterinarians, and breed and age estimates are based on a combination of professional input and our collective experience.  Our policy with information acquired prior to acceptance and while the dogs are in our care is that of "full disclosure".  It is our goal to ensure the adopter has all available information to ensure the best possible match between the dog and the adopter(s).  If we have identified a behavioral or health condition while the dog is in our care and custody, every effort will be made to correct it prior to adoption, OR the adopter will be made aware of the issue or condition prior to adoption.  Northern Lights' screening process is designed to identify only those adopters who are willing, and have the means, to treat conditions which may occur after adoption, and the adopter will be contractually responsible for doing so. However, Northern Lights' policy is to accept any adopted dog back into the program, at any time, for any reason.

animal.description: We were told Hooch was “spoiled rotten” by his previous owner, a man who had to give him up when he needed hospice care. He came to us two months ago from a temporary home where he “played too rough with their Great Dane” and was covered in scratches, scars, punctures and tears. After receiving weeks of medical care these wounds healed and he was neutered and brought up to date on vaccines.  He has a very negative/aggressive reaction to most everyone, except his current foster, when they come near his kennel or close to him when crated. He seems ok with most people outside of his kennel or crate but has not been socialized or allowed to get close to other people. He walks decently on a leash, usually sits when told, comes most of the time when called, like to ride in cars and will tolerate a muzzle pretty well. He becomes extremely agitated if you put a metal choke or prong collar on him. He show no food aggression with his foster and will play gently with her. He doesn’t seem to show aggression towards other dogs but knowing how chewed up he was, we have not put him with any. I don’t know his age. I don’t think he was ever socialized or trained.

animal.description:
This is Sophie!

Sophie is a special girl. She can be a little passive and more docile, but she is filled with unconditional love. With her hard life if does take time for her open up.

She is wonderful in a home. She is being fostered now and lives with small older dog and older kids but we're not sure how she'll do with other dogs and young children. We do know she does not do well around cats. She is loving, affectionate, smart and likes to play with toys.

She is a sable coat and brown eyes. She is medium sized with a short coat. Sophie would be great with a person or family who can give her lots of love, time, and patience to let the true Sophia come out.

Even with a hard life, Sophie is so smart, likes to play and is a super girl. She's patiently waiting for her fur-ever family so she can show you some unconditional love. If you think this family may be you, if so please fill out an adoption application at www.doggiebonez.com so that we can schedule a meet and greet. She is also on all of our social media pages IG: @Doggie_Bonez_Inc_ and Facebook: Doggie Bonez.

If adoption isn't an option, please consider fostering one of our pups. We are a volunteer run non-profit dog rescue and always welcome new short and/or long term doggie foster families. We greatly appreciate the help and time of our fosters. You provide all the love, comfort and safety of a home and we supply you with everything else you may need, dog food, dog bed, toys, medical attention (if needed) etc. If you are interested please visit www.doggiebonez.com to see all of our available dogs who need a foster family while waiting for their fur-ever home and complete the foster application.

animal.description:
Angel is thought to be a Mountain Feist who is 3-4 years old. She must have been dumped as a young puppy as she is not socialized to humans. She was trapped running with two larger dogs. The dogs hunted chickens and cats to survive. We are so grateful that Angel got into the trap because the other two dogs were shot and killed by irate neighbors.

Angel is 28 lbs and very healthy. She is stout and compact and would be great as a hiking companion or just a good little dog to sleep in your bed.
Angel is making slow progress in becoming a pet. We have  built a good relationship and I can touch her all over and pick her up. She is still not used to a leash but she comes when called and is very obedient. She is very food motivated and that will be the key to continuing her socialization. 

Angel lives at a pet hotel and is exposed to many dogs each day. She is playful and confident with other dogs. She is very fond of our 15 year old Lab mix. She sleeps with her and eats with her and generally takes comfort in being near her.

Angel will take treats from strangers but that's as far as we have gotten. Let’s face it Angel needs a lot of work. She will need a patient, competent leader to continue her progress. 

Adoption Fee $50

Post for Susan

animal.description:
Medical costs to date: $2,128.25

We have never wavered from our original Mission Statement (Dated 2004) of helping Scotties no matter their age or health concerns. Skyler is proof of our continued commitment to the dogs that are many times left behind.

If you can help us in any way with a donation, please give what you can. We have had several high-cost illnesses and a major surgery with our long term rescues. Please help us so we can continue to help them.

2-1-21: Skyler returned to the vet today for additional urinary issues, including leaking when sleeping. He is starting another round of antibiotics and will begin taking an incontinence medication twice a day.

1-8-21: We are happy to report Skyler is doing better after starting antibiotics, but we will continue to monitor him closely.

1-5-21: Skyler began urinating blood today and having problems defecating. We immediately rushed him to our wonderful vets. After an exam, x-rays, and ultrasound, it was determined his prostate is greatly enlarged and his bladder walls are thickened. No urinary infection was found, but these are not always readily detectible. Antibiotics and pain medication have been started. He is now back at his foster home with his girlfriend Shelby (our blind rescue Scot). He will spend the night in a room with sealed flooring, so he can have accidents that can easily be cleaned. We want to encourage him to relieve himself whenever he feels the need during the night. We are hoping this is just a small setback, however, it could also be the beginning of more serious issues. He will return to the vet in 10-14 days (sooner if he is not responding to the medications). We are concerned with his health, but optimistic our most senior Scot is on the mend.

9-2-20: Skyler continues to amaze us. At his age, he remains quite active (with a little help from joint supplements). He has befriended our blind Scottie girl "Shelby" and they are quite the pair.

5-20-20: Skyler's pathology report was inconclusive with the oral mass that was sent out for analysis.

5-14-20 Skyler required a dental cleaning today due to some painful areas in his mouth. Despite having good results from dental x-rays and the cleaning, there was one area of concern that had the doctor remove one of his canine teeth and send to a pathologist for analysis. Once the results are received, we will post more here. Obviously, any area of concern with a 15-1/2 year old Scottie is troubling, but we will await the pathology report.

This handsome wheaten boy came to us through absolutely no fault of his own. He has been loved by the same family since he was a pup. Skyler is 15-1/2 yo and has had lifelong medical care. In addition, we have just had a full senior exam performed, including x-rays and ultra-sound, blood tests, urinalysis and fecal. The blood tests revealed some abnormal liver values, which led us to an ultra-sound of his liver. A biopsy revealed possible cancer, but only major surgery would reveal the true problem. In collaboration with our vets, we have declined surgery for Skyler, due to his age, a heart murmur and the possibility of spreading cancer cells to other organs. Even if we proceeded with surgery, there is only a very small chance surgery would remove the mass, hence our collective decision.

Skyler's favorite pass-time is being near someone. He will follow you around the house, help you cook meals (hoping you will drop a tidbit) and lay at your feet when you are at a desk or computer. Such a love bug!

Our commitment to dogs like Skyler cannot be fulfilled without your help. If you care to donate to Skyler's medical and fostering care, it would be appreciated.

Donations may be made via www.paypal.com to email address:

Donate@scottiekingdom.com

or via USPS, to PO Box 551265 ~ Dallas, TX 75355

- - - - - - -

All dogs adopted by Scottie Kingdom Rescue, Inc. have had a full medical exam by one of our licensed Veterinarians, which includes testing (and treatment, if necessary) for Heartworm disease, Lyme disease, Ehrlichia and Anaplasmosis, all necessary vaccinations, spay/neuter surgery, dental cleaning as necessary, microchipping, registration of the microchip, and any other medical needs each particular dog may need. Copies of all available medical records are transferred to you when the adoption is finalized.

We prefer to adopt to families with past Scottie, Westie, Terrier experience, but realize this isn't always possible. We do NOT ship our pets. If you have that special place in your heart, and in your home, for a Scottie (or any of our other available rescue dogs), please visit us in Dallas for an in person meet & greet session with our available dogs. If you have existing dogs, they should travel to Dallas with you, so we can be assured that they will be compatible with the new addition to your family.

Please contact us at
Rescue@scottiekingdom.com
to receive an Adoption Application or for more information on our Adoption process. Also, please take the time to visit our website
www.scottiekingdom.com
for additional information.

We sometimes receive several applications on the same dog. Our goal is to place the dog in the best home possible, based on his/her needs, personality and past history. Please note: Adoptions are not done on a first come, first served basis. Submitting an application does not guarantee the adoption of any dog. We are looking for the best available home for each of our rescue dogs.

Thank you for your understanding, and for considering adoption!

We are
not
supported by your tax dollars or public grants, rather, we rely on donations to help us continue our rescue work for animals that are in need.

Donations may be made via PayPal to email address:

Donate@scottiekingdom.com

or via USPS, to PO Box 551265 ~ Dallas, TX

75355

animal.special_needs_notes: Kaya was very sick when she came to rescue.  She had a ureter that was not attached to her bladder and urine dripped straight through her.  She also had entropion which caused a lot of irritation on her eye.  She had multiple studies on her bladder and eventually a very extensive surgery to reattach her ureter.  She also had surgery to repair her eye condition.  Currently Kaya is health and happy and we are looking for a medical home.  She no longer drains urine straight through her, but does have some mild dripping of urine onto her fur.  She squats and pees otherwise like a normal dog.  Due to the dripping though, we had made a decision to keep her as a sanctuary dog.  We have rethought this decision and wanted to reach out for a medical home where Kaya can still live a normal life without having to remain in a kennel the rest of her life.  We are seeking a special home that can manage a dog with this condition.  It requires wiping off probably once daily any damp fur and otherwise she is an energetic, mid energy girl who loves being outside exploring.

animal.description:
My name is Mustang! My pack and I are from the south and were brought to Pets Alive. I am currently in a behavioral program here! This is helping me with manners, leash walking, playing with other dogs and people. I have amazing volunteers and staff who work with me towards improving my behavior and exploring my needs. My brothers and sisters have been worked with to be domesticated and have been successful with Pets Alive's adoptability program, and they've all been adopted! I am a great candidate for a sponsorship to get me the help I need through our training program!

To sponsor me, this is the link to learn more! http://petsalive.org/sponsor.html
